# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ironclad-warship
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] The **18-pounder long gun** was an intermediary calibre piece of naval artillery mounted on warships of the Age of Sail.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] They were used as main guns on the most typical frigates of the early 19th century, on the second deck of third-rate ships of the line, and even on the third deck of late first-rate ships of the line.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] As the 18-pounder calibre was consistent with both the French and the British calibre systems, it was used in many European navies between the 17th and the 19th century.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] It was a heavy calibre for early ships of the line, arming, for instance, the main batteries of *Couronne* in 1636.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] From the late 18th century, the French Navy used the 18-pounder in three capacities: as the main gun on frigates, as the battery on the upper gundeck of two-deckers, and lastly on the top deck of three-deckers.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] French frigates began carrying the 18-pounder under Louis XV, when the two *Pourvoyeuse*-class frigates, originally designed to carry 24-pounders, were equipped with it; at the time, a typical frigate would carry 12-pounders.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] Under Louis XVI, from 1779, the 18-pounder gradually became the standard calibre for frigates, starting with the *Hébé* class.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] These frigates were built on standard patterns designed by Jacques-Noël Sané, carrying 26, and later 28 main guns, complemented with smaller pieces on the forecastle.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] Around 130 of these frigates were built.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] At the end of the First French Empire, 24-pounder frigates began supplanting the 18-pounder frigates.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] Frigates built after the Bourbon Restoration used a different artillery system, one involving 30-pounders.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] On two-deckers, the 18-pounder was mounted on the upper deck as secondary artillery, to complement the 36-pounder main artillery on the lower deck.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] A 74-gun would carry thirty 18-pounders; this lighter secondary battery added firepower to the ship without raising the centre of gravity too much.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] Three-deckers used 36-pounders on their lower decks and 24-pounders on their second deck.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] During the First French Empire, 18-pounders would also arm Type 1 Model Towers for coastal defence.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] After introduction of rifled artillery in the middle 19th century, long 18-pounders were converted into so-called "14 cm n° 1 rifled muzzle-loaders Model 1864", by etching grooves on the inside of the barrel.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] James mentions 6 different 18-pounder guns in the early 1720s.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 9 ft appears in a diagram from about 1735, where its weight was listed as 41 hundredweight 1 quarter 8 pounds.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] The 1743 mensuration contains an 18-pounder of the same length and weight, with very similar dimensions.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] In tests in Minorca, one of the 18-pounders used was 9 ft long and weighed 39 hundredweight 1 quarter 3 pounds.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] 3 guns of 9 feet length from the reign of George II (1727–1760) currently survive at the Gut of Digby in Nova Scotia.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] Their dimensions are similar to the gun in the 1735 diagram.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] Adye's notebook from 1766 has an 18-pounder of 9 ft with almost identical dimensions to that in the 1735 diagram and 1743 mensuration.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] The establishment of 1764 mentioned an 18-pounder gun of 9 ft and 40 hundredweight.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] Walton included a gun with this length and weight in his table of dimensions in 1780, with similar dimensions to the 9 ft gun in the 1743 mensuration and the 1766 notebook.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] Adye's manuals of 1801 and 1813 mention the 9 ft 40 hundredweight 18-pounder, though by then it was being superseded by the newer Blomefield guns.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 9+1⁄2 ft is mentioned in Walton's table of dimensions in 1780, where its weight was 42 hundredweight.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] It also appears in Adye's manuals of 1801 and 1813, when it was also being superseded by Blomefield pattern guns.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 11 ft is first mentioned in tests in Minorca, where its weight was given as 51 hundredweight 5 pounds.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] In 1820, 6 iron 18-pounders are mentioned, with weights from 50 to 54+1⁄4 hundredweight.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] In 1857, an 18-pounder of 11 ft, "O.P" (old pattern) was in the list of guns submitted to the Committee on Ordnance.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] The guns of 9 feet 42+1⁄2 hundredweight and 8 feet 37+3⁄4 hundredweight were widely used as siege and garrison guns in addition to their naval role.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] As a siege gun, the 18-pounder served the same role as the Canon de 16 Gribeauval.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 9 feet 42+1⁄2 hundredweight was used on the upper deck of 74-gun ships of the line.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 8 feet 37+3⁄4 hundredweight was used on the main deck of 46- and 42-gun frigates.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] In 1825 Mould noted the gun of 6 feet 27 hundredweight was "not used at present." Although the guns of 6 feet 20 hundredweight and 5+1⁄2 feet 15 hundredweight were bored-up from Blomefield guns, an 1865 report mentions that they were designed by Alexander Dickson (Blomefield's successor).
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] William Congreve designed an 18-pounder gun patterned after his 24-pounder gun, after the latter proved successful in trials in 1813.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] It was 6 feet 10 inches in length and 32 hundredweight.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] It had the same conical shape with more metal around the breech, and trunnions further to the rear.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] 8 pieces were mentioned in lists submitted to the Committee on Ordnance in 1857, though it may have only been experimental.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] The guns retained were Blomefield or Dickson pattern guns mentioned above, as were the guns of 6 feet and 7 feet to be abolished.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 6 feet 10 inches was a Congreve gun.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] The gun of 9 feet 40 hundredweight is not known, but it may have been the old 18-pounder of 9 feet from the establishment of 1764.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] The Royal Navy used the 18-pounder on frigates, which carried 28 guns.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] Fourth-rate ships carried 26 on their secondary batteries, and third rates carried 28.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] Unlike the French, the British used second rates, of 90 to 98 guns; the 90-gun vessels carried thirty 18-pounders on their middle deck, while the 98-gun vessels carried a total of sixty 18-pounders, distributed over both the second and the third deck.
[src:ironclad-warship/18-pounder-long-gun] First rates carried thirty-four 18-pounders on their third deck and 24-pounders on the middle deck.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] The **24-pounder long gun** was a heavy calibre piece of artillery mounted on warships of the Age of Sail.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] 24-pounders were in service in the navies of France, Spain, Great Britain, the Netherlands, Sweden, and the United States.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] They were comparable to the Canon de 24 Gribeauval used by the French Army as its largest piece of siege artillery.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] 24-pounders were used as main guns on the heaviest frigates of the early 19th century and on fourth-rate ships of the line, on the second deck of first-rate ships of the line, and on the second deck of a few large third-rates.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] The 24-pounder calibre was consistent with both the French and the British calibre systems, and was a widespread gun amongst nations between the 17th and the 19th century.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] From the late 18th century, the French Navy used the 24-pounder in two capacities: as main gun on frigates and 64-guns, or as secondary artillery on three-deckers and even enlarged versions two-deckers.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] The experiment was tried again in 1785 with *Pomone*, a successful design that opened the way to a standardisation on the 24-pounder frigate exemplified by the *Romaine* class.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] Overall, 14 of these heavy frigates were built between *Pomone* in 1785, and *Poursuivante* in 1798, each carrying between 24 and 30 24-pounders.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] After the Bourbon Restoration, frigates were built using a different artillery system, carrying 30-pounders.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] Two-deckers used the 24-pounder in two capacities: on the smallest two-deckers of 64 guns, the 24-pounder constituted the main artillery, with 26 pieces.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] Typical 74-gun vessels carried a 36-pounder main battery and an 18-pounder secondary battery, until the enlarged variant of the *Téméraire* class appeared in 1803, comprising *Vétéran* and *Cassard*.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] More significantly, the 24-pounder armed the secondary battery of all 80-gun ships of the line from 1749, when the *Soleil-Royal* introduced the practice, resulting in a two-decker with enough firepower to challenge a three-decker of the time.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] During the reign of Louis XIV, three-deckers were standardised on a 36-pounder main artillery and an 18-pounder secondary battery.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] From the mid-18th century, under Louis XV, the secondary battery was strengthened to 24-pounders, beginning with the *Sans-Pareil* design that yielded *Royal Louis*.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] The other capital ships of the era, *Ville de Paris*, flagship of François Joseph Paul de Grasse during the American War of Independence, and *Bretagne*, flagship at the Battle of Ushant, similarly carried 24-pounders as secondary batteries.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] The practices was continued with the *Océan* class and the *Commerce de Paris* class.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] During the First French Empire, 24-pounders would also arm Type 1 Model Towers for coastal defence.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] In the Royal Navy, the 24-pounder was similarly used on some heavy frigates, which carried 26 guns.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] Fourth-rate ships carried 22 on their secondary batteries, and third-rates carried 32.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] First-rates carried thirty-four 24-pounders on their middle deck.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] Ten surviving guns which are likely examples of the 91⁄2-foot version weigh between 48 and 493⁄4 hundredweight.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] These guns are very similar to the gun of 91⁄2 feet and 491⁄4 hundredweight which was detailed in the mensuration of 1743.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] One other 24-pounder is mentioned in sources from 1780 and later, specifically a gun of 10 feet and 52 hundredweight.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] It is unknown whether the gun was new or the same as the 10 foot 24-pounder mentioned above.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] Except the guns of 501⁄2, 473⁄4, 22, and 20 hundredweight, most of these guns were little used, and declared obsolete in 1865 by the War Department.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] The guns cast in 1813 were designed to be evaluated against William Congreve's new pattern of gun.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] The guns of 91⁄2 feet 501⁄2 hundredweight and 9 feet 473⁄4 hundredweight were highly regarded as siege guns and widely used in that role in addition to their naval use.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] The guns of 22 and 20 hundredweight were mostly used in casemates and flank defenses as replacements for 24-pounder carronades.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] In response to a desire for lighter 24-pounders that could still be double-shotted,William Congreve designed a radical new type of 24-pounder, which was shorter, lighter, and with more metal concentrated around the gun breech rather than the chase (gun barrel).
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] It had a muzzle similar to a carronade, and the breeching ring was discarded in favor of a hole in the center of the neck of the cascabel.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] Because the weight of the cannon was much farther back, the trunnions could also be cast much farther rearward than in a similar conventional cannon.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] The heavier gun was tested in HMS *Eurotas* in October 1813, and the lighter gun was tested on HMS *Pactolus* in February 1814.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] The results were so favorable (despite somewhat violent recoil) that 300 more guns were ordered, and by 1820, Congreve noted 700 guns as being cast.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] Congreve also suggested several other guns to be constructed according to his principle, including a 24-pounder of 8 feet and 50 hundredweight.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] However, the recoil of the guns when in service proved to be worse than the trials indicated, and they were withdrawn from service by 1830, except in East India Company service.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] That year, 800 24-pounders were bored-up to produce 32-pounders, and they remained in active service in that role past 1865.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] Congreve's other suggested guns were never used beyond the testing stage.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] These were similar to the Blomefield designs, but with a slightly smaller caliber of 5.792 instead of 5.823 inches.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] In addition, a number of guns designated "N.P." for New Pattern appear in the records of the Committee on Ordnance.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] Finally, a 24-pounder of either 4 ft 10 in (1.47 m) or 5 ft (1.5 m) and 18 cwt was mentioned, and it was declared obsolete in 1865 by the War Department.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] Images are available showing 24-pounder long guns as the main gun deck armament on the USS *Independence* as used during the American Revolution; and the USS *Constitution* and USS *Constellation* as two of the original six frigates of the United States Navy starting in 1797.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] From the War of 1812 until the 1840s, The U.S.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] Navy used three classifications: the gun proper, which had a barrel weight of 150 lb (68 kg) per pound of shot, the double-fortified gun which had a barrel weight of 200 lb (91 kg) per pound of shot, and the medium gun, which had a barrel weight of 100 lb (45 kg) per pound of shot.
[src:ironclad-warship/24-pounder-long-gun] By comparison, a carronade would have a barrel weight of 65 lb (29 kg) per pound of shot.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] The **68-pounder cannon** was an artillery piece designed and used by the British Armed Forces in the mid-19th century.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] The cannon was a smoothbore muzzle-loading gun manufactured in several weights firing projectiles of 68 lb (31 kg).
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] Colonel William Dundas designed the 112 cwt version in 1841 which was cast the following year.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] The most common variant, weighing 95 long cwt (4,800 kg), dates from 1846.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] It entered service with the Royal Artillery and the Royal Navy and saw active service with both arms during the Crimean War.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] Over 2,000 were made and it gained a reputation as the finest smoothbore cannon ever made.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] The gun was produced at a time when new rifled and breech loading guns were beginning to make their mark on artillery.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] At first the 68-pounder's reliability and power meant that it was retained even on new warships such as HMS *Warrior*, but eventually new rifled muzzle loaders made all smoothbore muzzle-loading guns obsolete.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] However, the large surplus stocks of 68-pounders were given new life when converted to take rifled projectiles; the cannon remained in service and was not declared obsolete until 1921.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] The cannon was designed in response to the need for heavier weaponry as armour on ships of the line improved.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] Colonel William Dundas, the government's Inspector of Artillery between 1839 and 1852, designed the cannon in 1846.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] It was cast by the Low Moor Iron Works in Bradford in 1847 and entered service soon after.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] Like numerous cannon before it, it was a cast iron smoothbore loaded from the muzzle.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] The cannon was relatively cheap to produce – the Royal Commission on the Defence of the United Kingdom estimated that each cannon cost approximately £167.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] Over 2000 were cast before 1861 and its exceptional durability, range and accuracy earned it a reputation as the finest smoothbore cannon ever made.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] The gun was a traditional muzzleloader; it needed to be loaded from the front end of the barrel.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] Before it could be loaded the bore of the barrel was cleaned with a sponge, after which a propellant charge (gunpowder in a cloth bag) was rammed down into the breech.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] This was followed by a projectile, often encased in wadding.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] The gun was primed (using a metal spike inserted through the vent that pierced the charge), and fired using a percussion cap (which ignited the charge and forced the projectile out of the barrel).
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] The estimated rate of fire of this weapon was between 55 and 70 seconds, though loading speed could be expected to fall off as crew became fatigued.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] The 68-pounder had an effective range of approximately 3,000 yd (2,700 m), however at its maximum elevation of 15 degrees it had a maximum range of 3,620 yd (3,310 m), a distance that the projectile would cover in 15 seconds.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] With a 16 lb (7.3 kg) powder charge (the "far" charge, although the gun was proofed to 25 lb charges) the cannon fired a 68 lb (31 kg) solid shot at a muzzle velocity of 1,579 ft/s (481 m/s).
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] The cannon could fire solid shot, explosive shells, grapeshot, case shot and "Martins Liquid Iron Shell" (thin walled shells filled with molten iron, intended to serve as heated shot).
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] Although the cannon's barrel bore was 8.12 inches (20.6 cm), both shot and shells were 7.92 inches (20.1 cm) in diameter.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] This allowed a windage gap of 0.1 in (0.25 cm) around the projectile; enough to aid the loading process, but not enough to seriously diffuse the propellant gasses.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] The official weight of the shot was listed at 68 lbs but in reality this varied according to the material of the shot itself; cast iron shot weighed 67 lb (30 kg), wrought iron shot and steel shot weighed 72 lb (33 kg), and chilled steel weighed 68 lb 8 oz (31.1 kg).
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] It was estimated that one 68-pound shot had the destructive power equivalent to five 32-pound shot.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] The explosive shells were primed with 4 lb (1.8 kg) of gunpowder.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] They were fitted with simple fuses that were ignited by the flash of the charge – early wooden fuses were eventually replaced by more reliable fuses designed by Captain Edward Boxer in 1849.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] The gun crew still had to gauge the best length of fuse for the range they were firing – ideally the shell should explode just before hitting its target.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] To prevent the shell exploding in the barrel it was fitted with a sabot to ensure the fuse faced away from the charge.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] On land a minimum crew of nine men (usually commanded by a non-commissioned officer) was required to fire the gun, which was normally mounted on a traversing gun carriage.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] On board a ship the gun crew could be doubled to 18 men who needed to traverse the gun carriage by hand, using hand spikes and rope tackles.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] The extra crew was because sailing ships usually only fired their cannon from one side of the deck.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] In the unlikely event of both sides being in action at once, nine men would be detached to man the gun opposite.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] In both cases the gun was elevated using wooden wedges driven under the breech of the barrel by brute force.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] It was aimed using an advanced hexagonal sighting mechanism marked with the elevation on one face and the gun's range (according to different weights of cartridge charges) on the other five faces.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] The cannon was put to use both on land and at sea.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] It was fitted to numerous Royal Navy warships of different sizes such as HMS *Queen*, *Odin*, *Victor Emmanuel*, *Sepoy* and the *Conqueror*-class ships of the line.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] Several of these ships saw action during the Crimean War where the 68-pounder was used extensively during the Siege of Sevastopol.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] Along with 32-pounders and Lancaster guns they were taken from their ship mountings and dragged up to siege batteries by the Naval Brigade, from where they regularly bombarded Russian positions for the next year.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] The cannon was also fitted in large numbers to the *Aetna*-class ironclad floating batteries, although these had little impact on the war.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] Most notably the 68-pounder was fitted to the *Warrior*-class ironclads *Warrior* and *Black Prince*.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] Originally it was intended to fit forty 68-pounders, primarily on one gun deck, but this specification changed during their building and they were finally equipped with twenty-six 68-pounders (13 on each side).
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] Alongside these, the ships were equipped with new rifled breech loading Armstrong guns of two types; 7 inch and 40 pounders.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] Although the Armstrong guns represented a new direction in artillery, the breech loading mechanism meant that they were unable to withstand the explosion of a heavy cartridge.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] Smaller cartridge charges were therefore required and the gun's muzzle velocity suffered as a result.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] Ironically the Armstrong Guns were therefore incapable of penetrating the armour fitted to the *Warrior*-class ships, while the 68-pounder (with its high muzzle velocity) could.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] As late as 1867 it was planned to fit the new *Plover*-class gunvessels with 68-pounders, but they were instead completed with a RML 7 inch gun and a RML 64 pounder 64 cwt gun.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] On land the 68-pounder was used extensively in British coastal defences constructed during the 1850s - notably at forts like Gomer and Elson defending Portsmouth, and Forts Victoria, Albert and Freshwater Redoubt defending the Needles Passage.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] The 1859 Royal Commission envisaged arming the numerous new forts they proposed with the 68-pounder cannon and costed for them accordingly.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] The introduction of the Armstrong gun initially led many to think that weapon would be used instead, but whilst the forts were being built, the Armstrong gun's weaknesses were exposed and the military reverted to using muzzle loaded weapons.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] However, the advantages of rifling and the Armstrong's wrought iron construction were retained, leading to a new design of artillery piece – rifled muzzle loaders.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] The introduction of rifled muzzle loaders (also classed as RMLs) rendered smoothbore guns largely obsolete.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] However, the 68-pounder and other smoothbores still existed in large numbers and various attempts were made to adapt the guns to fire new projectiles.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] Eventually Captain William Palliser patented a method of boring out the gun barrel and inserting a wrought iron rifled liner.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] This allowed rifled shot and shells to be fired from old smoothbore cannon and experiments revealed that it made them even more powerful than they had been before.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] Introduced in 1872, 68-pounders adapted in this way had a calibre of 6.29 inches (16.0 cm) and were known as a **RML 68-pounder**, or officially as the **RML 80-pounder 5 ton**.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] With a 10 lb (4.5 kg) powder charge they could fire an 80 lb (36 kg) projectile at a muzzle velocity of 1,240 feet per second (380 m/s).
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] They were deployed as coast defence and garrison artillery around the British Empire and remained in service until eventually declared obsolete in 1921.
[src:ironclad-warship/68-pounder] At least two 68 pounders were converted to 7 in (18 cm) 6.55 long tons (6.66 t; 7.34 short tons) RML guns, firing a 115 lb (52 kg) or 150 lb (68 kg) double shot.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The **Admiralty** was a department of the Kingdom of Great Britain and from 1801 of the Government of the United Kingdom that was responsible for the command of the Royal Navy.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] Historically, its titular head was the Lord High Admiral – one of the Great Officers of State.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] For much of its history, from the early 18th century until its abolition, the role of the Lord High Admiral was almost invariably put "in commission" and exercised by the Lords Commissioner of the Admiralty, who sat on the governing Board of Admiralty, rather than by a single person.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Admiralty was replaced by the Admiralty Board in 1964, as part of the reforms that created the Ministry of Defence and its Navy Department (later Navy Command).
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Admiralty was among the most important departments of the British Government, because of the Royal Navy's role in the expansion and maintenance of the English overseas possessions in the 17th century, the British Empire in the 18th century, and subsequently.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The modern Admiralty Board, to which the functions of the Admiralty were transferred in 1964, is a committee of the tri-service Defence Council of the United Kingdom.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] This Admiralty Board meets only twice a year, and the day-to-day running of the Royal Navy is controlled by a Navy Board (not to be confused with the historic Navy Board).
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] It is common for the various authorities now in charge of the Royal Navy to be referred to as simply 'The Admiralty'.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] Since 1964, the title of Lord High Admiral of the United Kingdom has been vested in the monarch; the title was awarded to Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh by Queen Elizabeth II on his 90th birthday in 2011 and remained with him until his death in 2021.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] There also continues to be a Vice-Admiral of the United Kingdom and a Rear-Admiral of the United Kingdom, both of which are honorary offices.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The office of Admiral of England (later Lord Admiral, and later Lord High Admiral) was created around 1400; there had previously been Admirals of the northern and western seas.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] King Henry VIII established the Council of the Marine—later to become the Navy Board—in 1546, to oversee administrative affairs of the naval service.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] Operational control of the Royal Navy remained the responsibility of the Lord High Admiral, who was one of the nine Great Officers of State.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] This management approach would continue in force in the Royal Navy until 1832.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] King Charles I put the office of Lord High Admiral into commission in 1628, and control of the Royal Navy passed to a committee in the form of the Board of Admiralty.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The office of Lord High Admiral passed a number of times in and out of commission until 1709, after which the office was almost permanently in commission (the last Lord High Admiral being the future King William IV in the early 19th century).
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] These principal officers came to be known as the Navy Board responsible for 'civil administration' of the navy, from 1546 to 1832.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] This structure of administering the navy lasted for 285 years, however, the supply system was often inefficient and corrupt its deficiencies were due as much to its limitations of the times they operated in.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The various functions within the Admiralty were not coordinated effectively and lacked inter-dependency with each other, with the result that in 1832, Sir James Graham abolished the Navy Board and merged its functions within those of the Board of Admiralty.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] At the time this had distinct advantages; however, it failed to retain the principle of distinctions between the Admiralty and supply, and a lot of bureaucracy followed with the merger.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] In 1860 saw big growth in the development of technical crafts, the expansion of more admiralty branches that really began with age of steam that would have an enormous influence on the navy and naval thought.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] Between 1860 and 1908, there was no real study of strategy and of staff work conducted within the naval service; it was practically ignored.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] All the Navy's talent flowed to the great technical universities.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] This school of thought for the next 50 years was exclusively technically based.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The first serious attempt to introduce a sole management body to administer the naval service manifested itself in the creation of the Admiralty Navy War Council in 1909.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] Following this, a new advisory body called the Admiralty War Staff was then instituted in 1912, headed by the Chief of the War Staff who was responsible for administering three new sub-divisions responsible for operations, intelligence and mobilisation.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The new War Staff had hardly found its feet and it continually struggled with the opposition to its existence by senior officers they were categorically opposed to a staff.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The deficiencies of the system within this government department could be seen in the conduct of the Dardanelles campaign.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] There were no mechanisms in place to answer the big strategic questions.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] Sir John Jellicoe came to the Admiralty in 1916.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] He reorganised the war staff as following: Chief of War Staff, Operations, Intelligence, Signal Section, Mobilisation, Trade.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] It was not until 1917 that the admiralty department was again properly reorganised and began to function as a professional military staff.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] In May 1917, the term "Admiralty War Staff" was renamed and that department and its functional role were superseded by a new "Admiralty Naval Staff"; in addition, the newly created office of Chief of the Naval Staff was merged in the office of the First Sea Lord.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] Also appointed was a new post, that of Deputy Chief of the Naval Staff, and an Assistant Chief of the Naval Staff; all were given seats on the Board of Admiralty.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] This for the first time gave the naval staff direct representation on the board; the presence of three senior naval senior members on the board ensured the necessary authority to carry through any operation of war.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Deputy Chief of Naval Staff would direct all operations and movements of the fleet, while the Assistant Chief of Naval Staff would be responsible for mercantile movements and anti-submarine operations.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The office of Controller would be re-established to deal with all questions relating to supply; on 6 September 1917, a Deputy First Sea Lord, was added to the Board who would administer operations abroad and deal with questions of foreign policy.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] In October 1917, the development of the staff was carried one step further by the creation of two sub-committees of the Board—the Operations Committee and the Maintenance Committee.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The First Lord of the Admiralty was chairman of both committees, and the Operations Committee consisted of the First Sea Lord and Chief of Naval Staff, the Deputy First Sea Lord, Assistant Chief of Naval Staff, and Fifth Sea Lord.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] Full operational control of the Royal Navy was finally handed over to the Chief of Naval Staff (CNS) by an order in Council, effective October 1917, under which he became responsible for the issuing of orders affecting all war operations directly to the fleet.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] It also empowered the CNS to issue orders in their own name, as opposed to them previously being issued by the Permanent Secretary of the Admiralty in the name of the Board.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] In 1964, the Admiralty—along with the War Office and the Air Ministry—were abolished as separate departments of state, and placed under one single new Ministry of Defence.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] Within the expanded Ministry of Defence are the new Admiralty Board which has a separate Navy Board responsible for the day-to-day running of the Royal Navy, the Army Board and the Air Force Board, each headed by the Secretary of State for Defence.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] In order to deliver this the Naval Staff was organised into specialist Divisions and Sections.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] When the Admiralty unified with the Ministry of Defence in 1964 they were re designated as Directorates of the Naval Staff.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Admiralty Departments, which provides the men, ships, aircraft and supplies to carry out the approved policy.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The departments are superintended by the various offices of the Sea Lords.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Department of the Permanent Secretary which was the general co-ordinating agency, regulating naval finance, providing advice on policy, conducing all correspondence on behalf of the Board and maintaining admiralty records.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] Its primary component to deliver this is the Admiralty Secretariat, sections of the Secretariat (other than those which provide Common Services) were known as Branches.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Board of Admiralty consisted of a number of Lords Commissioners of the Admiralty.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Lords Commissioners were always a mixture of admirals, known as Naval Lords or Sea Lords and Civil Lords, normally politicians.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The quorum of the Board was two commissioners and a secretary.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The president of the Board was known as the First Lord of the Admiralty, who was a member of the Cabinet.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] After 1806, the First Lord of the Admiralty was always a civilian, while the professional head of the navy came to be (and is still today) known as the First Sea Lord.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Lords Commissioners of the Admiralty were the members of The Board of Admiralty, which exercised the office of Lord High Admiral when it was not vested in a single person.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The commissioners were a mixture of politicians without naval experience and professional naval officers, the proportion of naval officers generally increasing over time.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The First Sea Lord and Chief of Naval Staff was the Chief Naval Adviser on the Board of Admiralty to the First Lord and superintended the offices of the sea lords and the admiralty naval staff.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Navy Board was an independent board from 1546 until 1628 when it became subordinate to, yet autonomous of the Board of Admiralty until 1832.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] Its principal commissioners of the Navy advised the board in relation to civil administration of the naval affairs.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Navy Board was based at the Navy Office.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] Office of the Additional Civil Lord of the Admiralty.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] Office of the Parliamentary and Financial Secretary to the Admiralty.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] It evolved from *Admiralty Navy War Council, (1909–1912) which in turn became the Admiralty War Staff, (1912–1917) before finally becoming the Admiralty Naval Staff in 1917.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] It was the former senior command, operational planning, policy and strategy department within the British Admiralty.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] Office of the Vice Chief of the Naval Staff.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] Offices of the Assistant Chiefs of the Naval Staff.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Secretary's Department consisted of members of the civil service it was directed and controlled by a senior civil servant Permanent Secretary to the Board of Admiralty he was not a Lord Commissioner of the Admiralty, he functioned as a member of the board, and attended all of its meetings.
[src:ironclad-warship/admiralty-united-kingdom] In some cases, the term *admiralty* is used in a wider sense, as meaning *sea power* or *rule over the seas*, rather than in strict reference to the institution exercising such power.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The **Adriatic Sea** (/ˌeɪdriˈætɪk/) is a body of water separating the Italian Peninsula from the Balkan Peninsula.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic is the northernmost arm of the Mediterranean Sea, extending from the Strait of Otranto (where it connects to the Ionian Sea) to the northwest and the Po Valley.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The countries with coasts on the Adriatic are Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia, Italy, Montenegro, and Slovenia.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic contains more than 1,300 islands, mostly located along its eastern coast.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] It is divided into three basins, the northern being the shallowest and the southern being the deepest, with a maximum depth of 1,233 metres (4,045 ft).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The prevailing currents flow counterclockwise from the Strait of Otranto.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Tidal movements in the Adriatic are slight, although larger amplitudes occur occasionally.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic's salinity is lower than the Mediterranean's because it collects a third of the fresh water flowing into the Mediterranean, acting as a dilution basin.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The surface water temperatures generally range from 30 °C (86 °F) in summer to 12 °C (54 °F) in winter, significantly moderating the Adriatic Basin's climate.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic Sea sits on the Apulian or Adriatic Microplate.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] In the Late Oligocene, the Italian Peninsula first formed, separating the Adriatic Basin from the rest of the Mediterranean.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The western coast is alluvial or terraced, while the eastern coast is highly indented with pronounced karstification.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] There are dozens of marine protected areas in the Adriatic, designed to protect the sea's habitats and biodiversity—more than 7,000 species are identified as native to the Adriatic, many of them endemic, rare and threatened ones.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic's shores are populated by more than 3.5 million people; the largest cities are Bari, Venice, Trieste and Split.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Early settlements on the Adriatic shores were Etruscan, Illyrian, and Greek.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] By the 2nd century BC, the region was under Rome's control.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] In the Middle Ages, the sea was controlled, to a varying extent, by a series of states—most notably the Byzantine Empire, the Croatian Kingdom, the Republic of Venice, the Habsburg monarchy and the Ottoman Empire.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Napoleonic Wars resulted in the Austrian Empire gaining control of most of the eastern Adriatic shore and the Po Valley, while the Kingdom of Italy gradually took control of the remaining Italian coast during the 19th century.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Following the collapse of Austria-Hungary in 1918, control of the eastern coast passed to Yugoslavia and Albania, which agreed on their maritime boundaries with Italy in 1975 and 1992 respectively.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] After Yugoslavia's dissolution during the 1990s, its four coastal successor states—Slovenia, Croatia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and Montenegro—continued to recognise the previous maritime border with Italy, but have disputed the borders between themselves.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Fisheries and tourism are significant sources of income along the Adriatic coast.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Maritime transport is also a significant branch of the area's economy—there are 19 seaports in the Adriatic that each handle more than a million tonnes of cargo per year.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The largest Adriatic seaport by annual cargo turnover is the Port of Trieste, while the Port of Split is the largest by passengers served per year.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The origins of the name *Adriatic* are linked to the Etruscan settlement of Adria, which probably derives its name from Illyrian *adur* 'water, sea'.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] In classical antiquity, the sea was known as *Mare Adriaticum* (*Mare Hadriaticum*, also sometimes simplified to *Adria*) or, less frequently, as *Mare Superum* '[the] upper sea'.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The two terms were not synonymous, however.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] *Mare Adriaticum* generally corresponds to the Adriatic Sea's extent, spanning from the Gulf of Venice to the Strait of Otranto.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] That boundary became more consistently defined by Roman authors—early Greek sources place the boundary between the Adriatic and Ionian seas at various places ranging from adjacent to the Gulf of Venice to the southern tip of the Peloponnese, eastern shores of Sicily and western shores of Crete.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] *Mare Superum* on the other hand normally encompassed both the modern Adriatic Sea and the sea off the Apennine peninsula's southern coast, as far as the Strait of Sicily.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Another name used in the period was *Mare Dalmaticum*, applied to waters off the coast of Dalmatia or Illyricum.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] During the early modern period, the entire sea was also known as the **Gulf of Venice** (Italian: *golfo di Venezia*), although that name is now informally applied only to the northern area of the sea, from Maestra Point in the Po Delta to Cape Kamenjak on the Istrian Peninsula.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] In Serbo-Croatian and Slovene, the sea is often referred to as simply *Jadran*.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic Sea is a semi-enclosed sea, bordered in the southwest by the Apennine or Italian Peninsula, in the northwest by the Italian regions of Veneto and Friuli-Venezia Giulia, and in the northeast by Slovenia, Croatia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Montenegro, and Albania—the Balkan peninsula.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] In the southeast, the Adriatic Sea connects to the Ionian Sea at the 72-kilometre (45 mi) wide Strait of Otranto.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] It extends 800 kilometres (500 mi) from the northwest to the southeast and is 200 kilometres (120 mi) wide.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] It covers 138,600 square kilometres (53,500 sq mi) and has a volume of 35,000 cubic kilometres (8,400 cu mi).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic extends northwest from 40° to 45°47' north, representing the Mediterranean's northernmost portion.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The sea is geographically divided into the Northern Adriatic, Central (or Middle) Adriatic, and Southern Adriatic.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic Sea drainage basin encompasses 235,000 square kilometres (91,000 sq mi), yielding a land–sea ratio of 1.8.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The drainage basin's mean elevation is 782 metres (2,566 ft) above sea level, with a mean slope of 12.1°.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Major rivers discharging into the Adriatic include the Po, Soča, Krka, Neretva, Drin, Buna, and Vjosë.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] In the late 19th century, Austria-Hungary established a geodetic network with an elevation benchmark using the average Adriatic Sea level at the Sartorio pier in Trieste, Italy.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The benchmark was subsequently retained by Austria, adopted by Yugoslavia, and retained by the states that emerged after its dissolution.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] In 2016, Slovenia adopted a new elevation benchmark referring to the upgraded tide gauge station in the coastal town of Koper.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Alps, which also have a large meteorological impact on the Mediterranean, touch the Adriatic in the area around Trieste towards Duino and Barcola.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic Sea contains more than 1,300 islands and islets, most along the Adriatic's eastern coast—especially in Croatia, with 1,246 counted.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The number includes islands, islets, and rocks of all sizes, including ones emerging at ebb tide only.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Croatian islands include the largest—Cres and Krk, each covering about the same area of 405.78 square kilometres (156.67 sq mi)—and the tallest—Brač, whose peak reaches 780 metres (2,560 ft) above sea level.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The islands of Cres and the adjacent Lošinj are separated only by a narrow navigable canal dug in the time of classical antiquity; the original single island was known to the Greeks as Apsyrtides.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Croatian islands include 47 permanently inhabited ones, the most populous among them being Krk, Korčula and Brač.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The islands along the Adriatic's western (Italian) coast are smaller and less numerous than those along the opposite coast; the best-known ones are the 117 islands on which the city of Venice is built.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The northern shore of the Greek island of Corfu also lies in the Adriatic Sea as defined by the IHO.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The IHO boundary places the Diapontia Islands (northwest of Corfu) in the Adriatic Sea.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic Sea's average depth is 259.5 metres (851 ft), and its maximum depth is 1,233 metres (4,045 ft); however, the North Adriatic basin rarely exceeds a depth of 100 metres (330 ft).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The North Adriatic basin, extending between Venice and Trieste towards a line connecting Ancona and Zadar, is only 15 metres (49 ft) deep at its northwestern end; it gradually deepens towards the southeast.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] It is the largest Mediterranean shelf and is simultaneously a dilution basin and a site of bottom water formation.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Middle Adriatic basin is south of the Ancona–Zadar line, with the 270-metre (890 ft) deep Middle Adriatic Pit (also called the Pomo Depression or the Jabuka Pit).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The 170-metre (560 ft) deep Palagruža Sill is south of the Middle Adriatic Pit, separating it from the 1,200-metre (3,900 ft) deep South Adriatic Pit and the Middle Adriatic basin from the South Adriatic Basin.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Further on to the south, the sea floor rises to 780 metres (2,560 ft) to form the Otranto Sill at the boundary to the Ionian Sea.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The South Adriatic Basin is similar in many respects to the Northern Ionian Sea, to which it is connected.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The coast's ruggedness is exacerbated by the Dinaric Alps' proximity to the coast, in contrast to the opposite (Italian) coast where the Apennine Mountains are further away from the shoreline.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The coastal water dynamics are determined by the asymmetric coasts and the inflow of the Mediterranean seawater through the Straits of Otranto and further on along the eastern coast.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The smooth Italian coast (with very few protrusions and no major islands) allows the Western Adriatic Current, which is composed of the relatively freshwater mass on the surface and the cold and dense water mass at the bottom, to flow smoothly.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The coastal currents on the opposite shore are far more complex owing to the jagged shoreline, several large islands and the proximity of the Dinaric Alps to the shore.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The last produces significant temperature variations between the sea and the hinterland, which leads to the creation of local jets.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The tidal movement is normally slight, usually remaining below 30 centimetres (12 in).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The amphidromic point is at the mid-width east of Ancona.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The normal tide levels are known to increase significantly in a conducive environment, leading to coastal flooding; this phenomenon is most famously known in Italy—especially Venice—as *acqua alta*.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Such tides can exceed normal levels by more than 140 centimetres (55 in), with the highest tide level of 194 centimetres (76 in) observed on 4 November 1966.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Such flooding is caused by a combination of factors, including the alignment of the Sun and Moon, meteorological factors such as sirocco related storm surges, and the basin's geometric shape (which amplifies or reduces the astronomical component).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Moreover, the Adriatic's long and narrow rectangular shape is the source of an oscillating water motion (French: *seiche*) along the basin's minor axis.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Finally, Venice is increasingly vulnerable to flooding due to coastal area soil subsidence.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Such unusually high tides resulting in flooding have also been observed elsewhere in the Adriatic Sea, and have been recorded in recent years in the towns of Koper, Zadar and Šibenik as well.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] It is estimated that the Adriatic's entire volume is exchanged through the Strait of Otranto in 3.4±0.4 years, a comparatively short period.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] (For instance, approximately 500 years are necessary to exchange all the Black Sea's water.) This short period is particularly important as the rivers flowing into the Adriatic discharge up to 5,700 cubic metres per second (200,000 cu ft/s).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] This rate of discharge amounts to 0.5% of the total Adriatic Sea volume, or a 1.3-metre (4 ft 3 in) layer of water each year.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The greatest portion of the discharge from any single river comes from the Po (28%), with an average discharge from it alone of 1,569 cubic metres per second (55,400 cu ft/s).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] In terms of the annual total discharge into the entire Mediterranean Sea, the Po is ranked second, followed by the Neretva and Drin, which rank as third and fourth.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Another significant contributor of freshwater to the Adriatic is the submarine groundwater discharge through submarine springs (Croatian: *vrulja*); it is estimated to comprise 29% of the total water flux into the Adriatic.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The submarine springs include thermal springs, discovered offshore near the town of Izola.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The thermal spring water is rich with hydrogen sulfide, has a temperature of 22 to 29.6 °C (71.6 to 85.3 °F), and has enabled the development of specific ecosystems.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The inflow of freshwater, representing a third of the freshwater volume flowing into the Mediterranean, makes the Adriatic a dilution basin for the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Middle and South Adriatic Gyres (SAG), are significant cyclonic circulation features, with the former being intermittent and the latter permanent.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The SAG measures 150 kilometres (93 miles) in diameter.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] It contributes to the flow of bottom water from the Adriatic to the Levantine Basin through the Ionian Sea.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Through that process, the Adriatic Sea produces most of the East Mediterranean deep water.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic's surface temperature usually ranges from 22 to 30 °C (72 to 86 °F) in the summer, or 12 to 14 °C (54 to 57 °F) in the winter, except along the western Adriatic coast's northern part, where it drops to 9 °C (48 °F) in the winter.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The distinct seasonal temperature variations, with a longitudinal gradient in the Northern and transversal gradient in the Middle and Southern Adriatic, are attributed to the continental characteristics of the Adriatic Sea: it is shallower and closer to land than are oceans.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] During particularly cold winters, sea ice may appear in the Adriatic's shallow coastal areas, especially in the Venetian Lagoon but also in isolated shallows as far south as Tisno (south of Zadar).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Southern Adriatic is about 8 to 10 °C (14 to 18 °F) warmer during the winter than the more northerly regions.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic's salinity variation over the year is likewise distinct: it ranges between 38 and 39 PSUs, somewhat higher than the range of 32 to 37 PSUs for the open ocean.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The southern Adriatic is subjected to saltier water from the Levantine Basin.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] According to the Köppen climate classification, the upper half of the Adriatic is classified as humid subtropical climate (*Cfa*), with wetter summers and colder and drier winters, and the southern Adriatic are classified as hot-summer Mediterranean climate (*Csa*).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The air temperature can fluctuate by about 20 °C (36 °F) during a season.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The predominant winter winds are the bora and sirocco (called *jugo* along the eastern coast).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The bora is significantly conditioned by wind gaps in the Dinaric Alps bringing cold and dry continental air; it reaches peak speeds in the areas of Trieste, Senj, and Split, with gusts of up to 180 kilometres per hour (97 kn; 110 mph).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The sirocco brings humid and warm air, often carrying Saharan sand causing rain dust.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] On the Adriatic Sea's coasts and islands, there are numerous small settlements and a number of larger cities.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Among the largest are (counterclockwise) Trieste, Venice, Rimini, Ancona, Pescara and Bari in Italy; Vlorë and Durrës in Albania; Split, Zadar and Rijeka in Croatia; Koper in Slovenia.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] In total, more than 3.5 million people live on the Adriatic coasts.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] There are also some larger cities that are located very near the coast, such as the Italian cities of Ravenna and Lecce.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Venice, which was originally built on islands off the coast, is most at risk due to subsidence, but the threat is present in the Po delta as well.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The causes are a decrease in sedimentation rate due to loss of sediment behind dams, the deliberate excavation of sand for industrial purposes, agricultural use of water, and removal of ground water.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The sinking of Venice slowed after artesian wells were banned in the 1960s, but the city remains threatened by the *acqua alta* floods.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Recent studies have suggested that the city is no longer sinking, but a state of alert remains in place.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] In May 2003, then-Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi inaugurated the MOSE project (Italian: *Modulo Sperimentale Elettromeccanico*), an experimental model for evaluating the performance of inflatable gates.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The project proposes laying a series of 79 inflatable pontoons across the sea bed at the three entrances to the Venetian Lagoon.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] When tides are predicted to rise above 110 centimetres (43 in), the pontoons will be filled with air and block the incoming water from the Adriatic Sea.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] This engineering work was due to be completed by 2014, but as of November 2020 is expected to be completed in 2021.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] However, concern has been raised regarding the frequency of its use—while only necessary a few days a year, the worst-case sea level rise scenario between 2050 and 2100 would prompt deployment up to 187 days a year, essentially cutting off the Venetian Lagoon from the Adriatic Sea.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Among other possible adverse effects, this can be expected to lower the lagoon's oxygen levels and trap pollution inside of the city.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Geophysical and geological information indicate that the Adriatic Sea and the Po Valley are associated with a tectonic microplate—identified as the Apulian or Adriatic Plate—that separated from the African Plate during the Mesozoic era.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] This separation began in the Middle and Late Triassic, when limestone began to be deposited in the area.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Between the Norian and Late Cretaceous, the Adriatic and Apulia Carbonate Platforms formed as a thick series of carbonate sediments (dolomites and limestones), up to 8,000 metres (26,000 ft) deep.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Remnants of the former are found in the Adriatic Sea, as well as in the southern Alps and the Dinaric Alps, and remnants of the latter are seen as the Gargano Promontory and the Maiella mountain.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] In the Eocene and early Oligocene, the plate moved north and north-east, contributing to the Alpine orogeny (along with the African and Eurasian Plates' movements) via the tectonic uplift of the Dinarides and Alps.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] In the Late Oligocene, the motion was reversed and the Apennine Mountains' orogeny took place.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] An unbroken zone of increased seismic activity borders the Adriatic Sea, with a belt of thrust faults generally oriented in the northeast–southwest direction on the east coast and the northeast–southwest normal faults in the Apennines, indicating an Adriatic counterclockwise rotation.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] An active 200-kilometre (120 mi) fault has been identified to the northwest of Dubrovnik, adding to the Dalmatian islands as the Eurasian Plate slides over the Adriatic microplate.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Furthermore, the fault causes the Apennine peninsula's southern tip to move towards the opposite shore by about 0.4 centimetres (0.16 in) per year.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] If this movement continues, the seafloor will be completely consumed and the Adriatic Sea closed off in 50–70 million years.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] In the Northern Adriatic, the coast of the Gulf of Trieste and western Istria is gradually subsiding, having sunk about 1.5 metres (4 ft 11 in) in the past two thousand years.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] In the Middle Adriatic Basin, there is evidence of Permian volcanism in the area of Komiža on the island of Vis and the volcanic islands of Jabuka and Brusnik.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Earthquakes have been observed in the region since the earliest historical records.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] A recent strong earthquake in the region was the 1979 Montenegro earthquake, measuring 7.0 on the Richter scale.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Historical earthquakes in the area include the 1627 Gargano peninsula and the 1667 Dubrovnik earthquakes, both followed by strong tsunamis.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] In the last 600 years, fifteen tsunamis have occurred in the Adriatic Sea.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] All types of seafloor sediments are found in the Adriatic Sea.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Northern Adriatic's comparatively shallow seabed is characterised by relict sand (from times when the water level was lower and the area was a sandy beach), while a muddy bed is typical at depths below 100 metres (330 ft).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Sediments deposited in the Adriatic Sea today generally come from the northwest coast, being carried by the Po, Reno, Adige, Brenta, Tagliamento, Piave and Soča rivers.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The volume of sediments carried from the eastern shore by the Rječina, Zrmanja, Krka, Cetina, Ombla, Dragonja, Mirna, Raša and Neretva rivers is negligible, because these sediments are mostly deposited at the river mouths.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic's western shores are largely either alluvial or terraced, whereas the eastern shores are predominantly rocky, except for the southernmost part of the shore located in Albania that consists of sandy coves and rocky capes.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The eastern Adriatic shore's Croatian part is the most indented Mediterranean coastline.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Most of the eastern coast is characterised by a karst topography, developed from the Adriatic Carbonate Platform's exposure to weathering.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Karstification there largely began after the Dinarides' final uplift in the Oligocene and the Miocene, when carbonate deposits were exposed to atmospheric effects; this extended to the level of 120 metres (390 ft) below the present sea level, exposed during the Last Glacial Maximum.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] It is estimated that some karst formations are from earlier sea level drops, most notably the Messinian salinity crisis.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Similarly, karst developed in Apulia from the Apulian Carbonate Platform.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Rocks of the same type are found in Albania and on the western Adriatic coast.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] There are alternations of maritime and alluvial sediments occurring in the Po Valley, at the Adriatic's north-west coast, and as far west as Piacenza, dating to the Pleistocene as the sea advanced and receded over the valley.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] An advance began after the Last Glacial Maximum, which brought the Adriatic to a high point at about 5,500 years ago.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Since then, the Po delta has been prograding (expanding/extending).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The rate of coastal zone progradation between 1000 BC and 1200 AD was 4 metres (13 ft) per year.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] In the 12th century, the delta advanced at a rate of 25 metres (82 ft) per year.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] In the 17th century, the delta began to become a human-controlled environment, as the excavation of artificial channels started; the channels and new distributaries of the Po have been prograding at rates of 50 metres (160 ft) per year or more since then.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] There are more than 20 other rivers flowing into the Adriatic Sea in Italy alone, also forming alluvial coastlines, including the lagoons of Venice, Grado and Caorle.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] There are smaller eastern Adriatic alluvial coasts—in the deltas of the Dragonja, Buna and Neretva rivers.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic Sea is a unique water body in respect of its overall biogeochemical physiognomy.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] It exports inorganic nutrients and imports particulate organic carbon and nitrogen through the Strait of Otranto—acting as a mineralization site.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The exchange of the substances is made more complex by bathymetry of the Adriatic Sea—75% of water flowing north through the strait recirculates at the Palagruža Sill and North Adriatic adds no more than 3–4% of water to the South Adriatic.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] This is reflected in its biogeography and ecology, and particularly in the composition and properties of its ecosystems.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Its main biogeographic units are the Northern Adriatic, the Central Adriatic, and the Southern Adriatic.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The unique nature of the Adriatic gives rise to an abundance of endemic flora and fauna.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Croatian National Biodiversity Strategy Action Plan identified more than 7,000 animal and plant species in the Adriatic Sea.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Central Adriatic is especially abundant in endemic plant species, with 535 identified species of green, brown and red algae.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Four out of five Mediterranean seagrass species are found in the Adriatic Sea.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The most common species are *Cymodocea nodosa* and *Zostera noltii*, while *Zostera marina* and *Posidonia oceanica* are comparatively rare.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] This circulation has significantly contributed to the biodiversity of the countries along the eastern Adriatic coast; the common bottlenose dolphin is frequent in the eastern coast's waters only, and the Croatian coast provides refuge for the critically endangered monk seal and sea turtles.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Recent studies revealed that cetaceans and other marine megafaunas, that were once thought to be vagrants to Adriatic Sea, migrate and live in the semi-closed sea on larger scales.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Largest of these live normally is the fin whale, and sperm whale, the largest of toothed whales also migrate but less common than fin whales, followed by Cuvier's beaked whales.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Basking sharks and manta rays are some of migrant species to the sea.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Historical presences of depleted or extinct species such as North Atlantic right whales (extinct or functionally extinct), Atlantic gray whales (extinct), and humpback whales have been speculated as well.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Tuna has been caught by the locals in the upper Adriatic for thousands of years.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The very large schools consisted mainly of little tunny and moved as far as the Gulf of Trieste.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] However, increasing fishing prevented the migration of large schools of fish to the north.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The last major tuna catch was made there in 1954 by the fishermen from Santa Croce, Contovello and Barcola.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Northern Adriatic in particular is rich in endemic fish fauna.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Around thirty species of fish are found in only one or two countries bordering the Adriatic Sea.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] These are particularly due to or dependent upon the karst morphology of the coastal or submarine topography; this includes inhabiting subterranean habitats, karst rivers, and areas around freshwater springs.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] There are 45 known subspecies endemic to the Adriatic's coasts and islands.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] In the Adriatic, there are at least 410 species and subspecies of fish, representing approximately 70% of Mediterranean taxa, with at least 7 species endemic to the Adriatic.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Sixty-four known species are threatened with extinction, largely because of overfishing.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Only a small fraction of the fish found in the Adriatic are attributed to recent processes such as Lessepsian migration, and escape from mariculture.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The biodiversity of the Adriatic is relatively high, and several marine protected areas have been established by countries along its coasts.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] In Italy, these are Miramare in the Gulf of Trieste (in the Northern Adriatic), Torre del Cerrano and Tremiti Islands in the Middle Adriatic basin and Torre Guaceto in southern Apulia.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Miramare protected area was established in 1986 and covers 30 hectares (74 acres) of coast and 90 hectares (220 acres) of sea.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The area encompasses 1.8 kilometres (1.1 mi) of coastline near the Miramare promontory in the Gulf of Trieste.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Torre del Cerrano protected area was created in 2009, extending 3 nautical miles (5.6 km; 3.5 mi) into the sea and along 7 kilometres (4.3 mi) of coastline.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Various zones of the protected area cover 37 square kilometres (14 sq mi) of sea surface.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Tremiti Islands reserve has been protected since 1989, while the Tremiti islands themselves are part of the Gargano National Park.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Torre Guaceto protected area, located near Brindisi and Carovigno, covers a sea surface of 2,227 hectares (5,500 acres) and is adjacent to the Torre Guaceto State Reserve covering 1,114 hectares (2,750 acres) of coast and sharing an 8-kilometre (5.0 mi) coastline with the marine protected area.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Furthermore, there are 10 internationally important (Ramsar) wetland reserves in Italy located along the Adriatic coast.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Brijuni national park encompasses the 743.3-hectare (1,837-acre) archipelago itself and 2,651.7 hectares (6,552 acres) of surrounding sea; it became a national park in 1999.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Lim Canal is a 10-kilometre (6.2 mi) ria of the Pazinčica river.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Kornati national park was established in 1980; it covers approximately 220 square kilometres (85 sq mi), including 89 islands and islets.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The marine environment encompasses three-quarters of the total area, while the island shores' combined length equals 238 kilometres (148 mi).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Telašćica is a nature park established on Dugi Otok in 1988.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The park covers 69 kilometres (43 mi) of coastline, 22.95 square kilometres (8.86 sq mi) of land and 44.55 square kilometres (17.20 sq mi) of sea.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Bay of Mali Ston is located at the border of Croatia and Bosnia–Herzegovina, north of the Pelješac peninsula.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The marine protected area covers 48 square kilometres (19 sq mi).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Lastovo nature park was established in 2006, and it includes 44 islands and islets, 53 square kilometres (20 sq mi) of land and 143 square kilometres (55 sq mi) of sea surface.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Mljet national park was established in 1960, covering a 24-square-kilometre (9.3 sq mi) marine protection area.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] In addition, there is a Ramsar wetland reserve in Croatia—the Neretva river's delta.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] In Slovenia, the marine and coastal protected nature areas are the Sečovlje Salina Landscape Park, Strunjan Landscape Park, Škocjan Inlet Nature Reserve, and the Debeli Rtič, Cape Madona and Lakes in Fiesa natural monuments.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Sečovlje Salina Landscape Park was established in 1990, covers 721 hectares (1,780 acres), and includes four nature reserves.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] In 1993, the area was designated a Ramsar site; it is also a site of international importance for waterbird species.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The 429-hectare (1,060-acre) Strunjan Landscape Park was established in 2004 and comprises two nature reserves.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] It includes a 4 kilometres (2.5 mi) long cliff, the northernmost Mediterranean salt field and the only Slovenian lagoon system.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] It is also the northernmost point of growth of some Mediterranean plant species.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Škocjan Inlet Nature Reserve was established in 1998 and covers 122 hectares (300 acres).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Debeli Rtič natural monument covers 24 hectares (59 acres), the Cape Madona natural monument covers 12 hectares (30 acres), and the Lakes in Fiesa natural monument, with the coastal lake as the only brackish lake in Slovenia, covers 2.1 hectares (5.2 acres).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] In 2010, Albania established its first marine protection area, the Karaburun-Sazan National Marine Park at the Karaburun Peninsula where the Adriatic and Ionian Seas meet.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The park covers a total of 12,570 hectares (31,100 acres).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Two additional marine protection areas are planned in Albania: the Cape of Rodon (Albanian: *Kepi i Rodonit*) and Porto Palermo.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] In addition, Albania is home to two Ramsar wetland reserves: Karavasta Lagoon, and Butrint.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Neither Bosnia–Herzegovina nor Montenegro have or plan to establish any marine protection areas.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Adriatic Sea ecosystem is threatened by excessive input of nutrients through drainage from agricultural land and wastewater flowing from cities; this includes both along its coast and from rivers draining into the sea—especially from the Po River.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Venice is often cited as an example of polluted coastal waters where shipping, transportation, farming, manufacturing and wastewater disposal contribute to polluting the sea.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] A further risk is presented by ballast water discharge by ships, especially tankers.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Still, since most of the cargo handled by the Adriatic ports, and virtually all liquid (tanker) cargo handled by the ports, is coming to—not coming from—the Adriatic Basin, the risk from ballast water (from tankers expelling ballast water then loading in the Adriatic) remains minimal.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] However, proposed export oil pipelines were objected to specifically because of this issue.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Oil spills are a major concern in terms of potential environmental impact and damage to tourism and fisheries.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] It is estimated that if a major oil spill happened, a million people would lose their livelihoods in Croatia alone.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] An additional risk is presented by oil refineries in the Po River basin where oil spills have occurred before, in addition to accidents occurring in the Adriatic already, so far with no significant environmental consequences.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Since 2006, Italy has been considering the construction of an offshore and an onshore LNG terminal in the Gulf of Trieste, as well as a pipeline, in the immediate vicinity of the Slovenian–Italian border.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] The Slovenian government and municipalities, the municipal council of Trieste, and non-governmental organisations have voiced concern over their environmental hazards, effect on transport and effect on tourism.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Another source of pollution of the Adriatic is solid waste.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Drifting waste—occasionally relatively large quantities of material, especially waste plastic—is transported northwest by the sirocco.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Air pollution in the Adriatic Basin is associated with the large industrial centres in the Po River valley and the large industrial cities along the coast.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Italy and Yugoslavia established a joint commission to protect the Adriatic Sea from pollution in 1977; the organization later changed with Slovenia, Croatia and Montenegro replacing Yugoslavia.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] Future pollution hazards are addressed and pollution hotspots are assessed not only by nations in the basin but also through regional projects with World Bank support.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p01] 27 such hotspots have been determined as of 2011, 6 warranting an urgent response.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Settlements along the Adriatic dating to between 6100 and 5900 BC appear in Albania and Dalmatia on the eastern Adriatic coast, related to the Cardium pottery culture.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] During classical antiquity, Illyrians inhabited the eastern coast, and the western coast was inhabited by the peoples of Ancient Italy, mainly Etruscans, before the Roman Republic's rise.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Greek colonisation of the Adriatic dates back to the 7th and 6th centuries BC when the ancient cities of Epidamnos and Apollonia were founded.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The Greeks soon expanded further north establishing several cities, including Ancona, Black Corcyra, Epidaurus, Issa, with trade established as far north as the Po River delta, where an emporium (trading station) was founded in Adria.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Roman economic and military influence in the region began to grow with the creation by 246 BC of a major naval base at Brundisium (now Brindisi), which was established to bar Carthaginian ships from the Adriatic during the Punic Wars.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] This led to conflict with the Illyrians, who lived in a collection of semi-Hellenized kingdoms that covered much of the Balkans and controlled the eastern shore of the sea, resulting in the Illyrian Wars from 229 to 168 BC.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The initial Roman intervention in 229 BC, motivated in part by a desire to suppress Illyrian piracy in the Adriatic, marked the first time that the Roman navy crossed that sea to launch a military campaign.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Those wars ended with the eastern shore becoming a province of the Roman Republic.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] However, resistance to Roman rule continued sporadically and Rome did not completely consolidate control of the region until Augustus's general Tiberius put down the Great Illyrian Revolt, a bitter struggle waged from 6 to 9 AD.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Following the repression of the revolt the Roman province of Illyricum was split into Dalmatia and Pannonia.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] During the Roman period, Brundisium, on the western shore, and Apollonia and Dyrrachium (originally called Epidamnos, now Durrës in Albania) on the eastern shore became important ports.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Brundisium was linked by the Via Appia road to the city of Rome, and Dyrrachium and Apollonia were both on the Via Egnatia, a road that by about 130 BC the Romans had extended eastward across the Balkans to Byzantium (later Constantinople, now Istanbul).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] This made the sea passage across the Adriatic between Brundisium and Dyrrachium (or Apollonia) a link in the primary route for travelers, trade, and troop movements, between Rome and the East.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] This route played a major role in some of the military operations that marked the end of the Roman Republic and the start of the imperial period.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Sulla used it during the First Mithridatic War.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Marc Antony and Octavian (later Augustus) crossed the Adriatic to Dyrrachium with their armies in their campaign against two of Caesar's assassins, Brutus and Cassius, that culminated in the Battle of Philippi.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Brundisium and Dyrrachium remained important ports well after the Roman period, but an earthquake in the 3rd century AD changed the path of a river causing Apollonia's harbor to silt up, and the city to decline.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Another city on the Italian coast of the Adriatic that increased in importance during the Roman era was Ravenna.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] During the reign of Augustus, it became a major naval base as part of his program to re-organize the Roman navy to better protect commerce in the Mediterranean.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] During the 4th century AD the emperors of the Western Roman Empire had moved their official residence north from Rome to Mediolanum (now Milan) in order to be better able to control the military frontier with the Germanic tribes.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In 402 AD, during a period of repeated Germanic invasions of Italy, the capital was shifted to Ravenna because nearby marshes made it more defensible, and the Adriatic provided an easy escape path by sea.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] When the Western Empire fell in 476 AD Ravenna became the capital of the Ostrogothic Kingdom of Italy.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In the Early Middle Ages, after the Roman Empire's decline, the Adriatic's coasts were ruled by Ostrogoths, Lombards and the Byzantine Empire.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The Ostrogothic Kingdom ruled Italy following the fall of the Western Roman Empire in 476 AD.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] However, during the reign of Justinian the Byzantine Empire sent an army under the general Belisarius to regain control of Italy, resulting in the Gothic War (535–554).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The Byzantines established the Exarchate of Ravenna and by 553 AD their viceroy (Exarch) ruled almost the entire Italian peninsula from that city.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In 568 AD the Lombards invaded northern Italy, and over the course of the next century or so the importance of the Exarchate declined as the territory under Lombard control expanded and as the Byzantine outpost of Venice became increasingly independent.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In 752 AD the Lombards overthrew the Exarchate, ending the influence of the Byzantine Empire on the western shore of the Adriatic for a few centuries.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The Republic of Venice, one of the maritime republics, was founded during this period and went on to become a significant maritime power after receiving a Byzantine tax exemption in 1082.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The end of the period brought about the Holy Roman Empire's control over the Kingdom of Italy (which would last until the Peace of Westphalia in 1648), the establishment of an independent Kingdom of Croatia and the Byzantine Empire's return to the southern Apennine peninsula.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In addition, the Papal States were carved out in the area around Rome and central Italy in the 8th century.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In this period, the Republic of Venice began to expand its territory and influence.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In 1202, the Fourth Crusade was diverted to conquer Zadar at the behest of the Venetians—the first instance of a Crusader force attacking a Catholic city—before proceeding to sack Constantinople.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In the 13th century, Venice established itself as a leading maritime nation.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] During much of the 12th and 13th centuries, Venice and the Republic of Genoa were engaged in warfare culminating in the War of Chioggia, ousting the Genoese from the Adriatic.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Still, the 1381 Treaty of Turin that ended the war required Venice to renounce claims to Dalmatia, after losing the territory to Hungary in 1358.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In the same year, the Republic of Ragusa was established in Dubrovnik as a city-state after it was freed from Venetian suzerainty.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Venice regained Dalmatia in 1409 and held it for nearly four hundred years, with the republic's apex of trading and military power in the first half of the 15th century.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] These defeats spelled the end of an independent Hungarian kingdom, and both Croatian and Hungarian nobility chose Ferdinand I of the House of Habsburg as their new ruler, bringing the Habsburg monarchy to the shore of the Adriatic Sea, where it would remain for nearly four hundred years.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The Ottomans and Venetians fought a series of wars, but until the 17th century these were not fought in the Adriatic area.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Ottoman raids on the Adriatic coasts effectively ceased after the massive setback in the Battle of Lepanto in October 1571.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The 17th century's final territorial changes were caused by the Morean or Sixth Ottoman–Venetian War, when in 1699 Venice slightly enlarged its possessions in Dalmatia.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In 1797, the Republic of Venice was abolished after the French conquest.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The Venetian territory was then handed over to Austria and briefly ruled as part of the Archduchy of Austria.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The territory was turned back over to France after the Peace of Pressburg in 1805 when the territory in the Po valley became an integral part of the new Napoleonic Kingdom of Italy.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The new kingdom included the province of Romagna, thus removing the Papal State from the Adriatic coast; however, Trieste, Istria and Dalmatia were joined into a set of separate provinces of the French Empire: the Illyrian Provinces.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] These were created in 1809 through the Treaty of Schönbrunn; they represented the end of Venetian rule on the eastern Adriatic coast, as well as the end of the Republic of Ragusa.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The Adriatic Sea was a minor theatre in the Napoleonic Wars; the Adriatic campaign of 1807–1814 involved the Royal Navy contesting the Adriatic's control by the combined navies of France, Italy and the Kingdom of Naples.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] During the campaign, the British navy occupied Vis and established its base there in Port St.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The campaign reached its climax in the 1811 Battle of Lissa, and ended with British and Austrian forces seizing the coastal cities on the eastern Adriatic coast from the French.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Days before the Battle of Waterloo, the Congress of Vienna awarded the Illyrian Provinces (spanning from the Gulf of Trieste to the Bay of Kotor) to Austria.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The Congress of Vienna also created the Kingdom of Lombardy–Venetia which encompassed the city of Venice, the surrounding coast and a substantial hinterland, and was controlled by Austria.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In the Apennine peninsula's south, the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies was formed in 1816 by unifying the kingdoms of Naples and Sicily.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The process of Italian unification culminated in the Second Italian War of Independence, resulting in the Kingdom of Sardinia annexing all territories along the western Adriatic coast south of Venetia in 1860, and the 1861 establishment of the Kingdom of Italy in its place.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The Kingdom of Italy expanded in 1866: it annexed Venetia, but its navy was defeated in the Adriatic near Vis.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Following the Austro-Hungarian Compromise of 1867 and the Croatian–Hungarian Settlement of 1868, the control of much of the eastern Adriatic coast was redefined.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The cisleithanian (Austrian) part of Austria-Hungary spanned from the Austrian Littoral to the Bay of Kotor, with the exception of the Croatian Littoral mainland.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In the territory outside the Austrian Littoral, special status was given to Fiume (modern-day Rijeka) as a separate part of the Kingdom of Hungary.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The rest of the territory was made a part of the Kingdom of Croatia-Slavonia, which in turn was also in the Transleithanian part of the dual monarchy.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The Adriatic coastline controlled by the Ottoman Empire was reduced by the Congress of Berlin in 1878, through recognition of the independence of the Principality of Montenegro, which controlled the coast south of the Bay of Kotor to the Bojana River.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The Ottoman Empire lost all territories along the Adriatic following the First Balkan War and consequent 1913 Treaty of London that established an independent Albania.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The World War I Adriatic Campaign was largely limited to blockade attempts by the Allies and the effort of the Central Powers to thwart the British, French and Italian moves.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Italy joined the Allies in April 1915 with the Treaty of London, which promised Italy the Austrian Littoral, northern Dalmatia, the port of Vlorë, most of the eastern Adriatic islands and Albania as a protectorate.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The treaty provided the basis for all the following divisions between Italy and Yugoslavia.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In 1918, the Montenegrin national assembly voted to unite with the Kingdom of Serbia, giving the latter access to the Adriatic.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Another short-lived, unrecognised state established in 1918 was the State of Slovenes, Croats and Serbs, formed from parts of Austria-Hungary, comprising most of the former monarchy's Adriatic coastline.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Later that year, the Kingdom of Serbia and the State of Slovenes, Croats and Serbs formed the Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes—subsequently renamed Yugoslavia.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The proponents of the new union in the Croatian parliament saw the move as a safeguard against Italian expansionism as stipulated in the Treaty of London.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The treaty was largely disregarded by Britain and France because of conflicting promises made to Serbia and a perceived lack of Italian contribution to the war effort outside Italy itself.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The 1919 Treaty of Saint-Germain-en-Laye did transfer the Austrian Littoral and Istria to Italy but awarded Dalmatia to Yugoslavia.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Following the war, a private force of demobilized Italian soldiers seized Rijeka and set up the Italian Regency of Carnaro—seen as a harbinger of Fascism—in order to force the recognition of Italian claims to the city.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] During World War II, the Adriatic saw only limited naval action, starting with the Italian invasion of Albania and the joint Axis invasion of Yugoslavia.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The latter led to the annexation of a large part of Dalmatia and nearly all the eastern Adriatic islands by Italy and the establishment of two puppet states, the Independent State of Croatia and the Kingdom of Montenegro, which controlled the remainder of the former Yugoslav Adriatic coast.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In 1947, after the Armistice between Italy and Allied armed forces and the war's end, Italy (now a republic) and the Allies signed the Treaty of Peace with Italy.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The FTT was partitioned in 1954: Trieste itself and the area to the North of it were placed under Italian control, while the rest came under Yugoslav control.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] This arrangement was made permanent in the 1975 Treaty of Osimo.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] During the Cold War, the Adriatic Sea became the southernmost flank of the Iron Curtain as Italy joined NATO, while the Warsaw Pact established bases in Albania.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] After the fall of communism, Yugoslavia broke apart: Slovenia and Croatia declared independence in 1991, and Bosnia–Herzegovina followed in 1992, while Montenegro remained in a federation with Serbia, officially called Serbia and Montenegro.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The ensuing Croatian War of Independence included limited naval engagements and a blockade of Croatia's coast by the Yugoslav Navy, leading to the Battle of the Dalmatian channels and a later withdrawal of Yugoslav vessels.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Montenegro declared itself independent in 2006, effectively land-locking Serbia.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The period also saw the Adriatic Sea as the theatre of several NATO operations, including the blockade of Yugoslavia, intervention in Bosnia and Herzegovina and the 1999 bombing of Yugoslavia.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Italy and Yugoslavia defined their Adriatic continental shelf delimitation in 1968, with an additional agreement signed in 1975 on the Gulf of Trieste boundary, following the Treaty of Osimo.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The boundary agreed in 1968 extends 353 nautical miles (654 km; 406 mi) and consists of 43 points connected by straight lines or circular arc segments.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The additional boundary agreed upon in 1975 consists of 5 points, extending from an end point of the 1968 line.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] All successor states of former Yugoslavia accepted the agreements.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In the Adriatic's southernmost areas the border was not determined in order to avoid prejudicing the location of the tripoint with the Albanian continental shelf border, which remains undefined.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Before the breakup of Yugoslavia, Albania, Italy and Yugoslavia initially proclaimed 15-nautical-mile (28 km; 17 mi) territorial waters, subsequently reduced to international-standard 12 nautical miles (22 km; 14 mi) and all sides adopted baseline systems (mostly in the 1970s).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Albania and Italy determined their sea border in 1992 according to the equidistance principle.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Following Croatian EU membership, the Adriatic became an internal sea of the EU.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea defines the Adriatic Sea as an enclosed or semi-enclosed sea.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The Adriatic Euroregion was established in Pula in 2006 to promote trans-regional and trans-national cooperation in the Adriatic Sea area and serve as an Adriatic framework to help resolve issues of regional importance.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In addition, the maritime boundary between Albania and Montenegro was not defined before the 1990s.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Croatia and Slovenia started negotiations to define maritime borders in the Gulf of Piran in 1992 but failed to agree, resulting in a dispute.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Both countries also declared their economic zones, which partially overlap.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Croatia's application to become an EU member state was initially suspended pending resolution of its border disputes with Slovenia.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] These disputes with Slovenia were eventually settled with an agreement to accept the decision of an international arbitration commission set up via the UN, enabling Croatia to progress towards EU membership.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Croatia is still not following the resolution of the international arbitration for the Gulf of Piran.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] A dispute over the gulf is still on going with the Croatians handing out fines to Slovenian fishermen that are following the agreed economic.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Aside from the EU membership difficulty, even before its settling the dispute has caused no major practical problems.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The maritime boundary between Bosnia–Herzegovina and Croatia was formally settled in 1999, but a few issues are still in dispute—the Klek peninsula and two islets in the border area.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The Croatia–Montenegro maritime boundary is disputed in the Bay of Kotor, at the Prevlaka peninsula.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] This dispute was exacerbated by the peninsula's occupation by the Yugoslav People's Army and later by the (Serbian–Montenegrin) FR Yugoslav Army, which in turn was replaced by a United Nations observer mission that lasted until 2002.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Croatia took over the area with an agreement that allowed Montenegrin presence in the bay's Croatian waters, and the dispute has become far less contentious since Montenegro's independence in 2006.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The Adriatic Sea fishery's production is distributed among countries in the basin.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In 2000, the nominal—on a live weight basis—total landings of all Adriatic fisheries reached 110,000 tonnes (108,000 long tons).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Overfishing is a recognised problem—450 species of fish live in the Adriatic Sea, including 120 species threatened by excessive commercial fishing, a problem exacerbated by pollution and global warming.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Overexploited species include common dentex, red scorpionfish, monkfish, John Dory, blue shark, spiny dogfish, mullet, red mullet, Norway lobster, as well as European hake, and sardines.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Turtles and common bottlenose dolphins are also being killed by fishing nets.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The depleted fish stock, and Croatia's Ecological and Fisheries Protection Zone (ZERP) contributed to accusations of overfishing exchanged between Italian and Croatian fishermen.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] ZERP was introduced in 2003, but its application to EU member states was suspended in 2004.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The depleted stocks of fish are being addressed through a new proposed EU fisheries policy that was scheduled to take effect in 2013, when Croatia acceded to the EU, and restore the stocks to sustainable levels by 2015.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The largest volume of fish harvesting was in Italy, where the total production volume in 2007 stood at 465,637 tonnes (458,283 long tons).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In 2003, 28.8% of Italian fisheries production volume was generated in the Northern and central Adriatic, and 24.5% in Apulia (from the Southern Adriatic and Ionian Sea).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Italian fisheries, including those operating outside the Adriatic, employed 60,700 in the primary sector, including aquaculture (which comprises 40% of the total fisheries production).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The total fisheries output's gross value in 2002 was $1.9 billion.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In 2007, Croatia's production in live weight reached 53,083 tonnes (52,245 long tons).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In 2006, the total Croatian fisheries production volume was 37,800 tonnes (37,200 long tons) of catch and 14,200 tonnes (14,000 long tons) from marine aquaculture.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Croatian fisheries employed approximately 20,000.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Croatian marine aquaculture production consisted of tuna (47.2%), oysters and mussels (28.2% combined) and bass and bream (24.6% combined).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In 2007, Albanian fisheries production amounted to 7,505 tonnes (7,386 long tons), including aquaculture production, which reached 1,970 tonnes (1,940 long tons) in 2006.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] At the same time, Slovenian fisheries produced a total of 2,500 tonnes (2,460 long tons) with 55% of the production volume originating in aquaculture, representing the highest ratio in the Adriatic.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Finally, the Montenegrin fisheries production stood at 911 tonnes (897 long tons) in 2006, with only 11 tonnes coming from aquaculture.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In 2007, the fisheries production in Bosnia–Herzegovina reached volume of 9,625 and 2,463 tonnes (9,473 and 2,424 long tons) in Slovenia.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The countries bordering the Adriatic Sea are significant tourist destinations.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The largest number of tourist overnight stays and the most numerous tourist accommodation facilities are recorded in Italy, especially in the Veneto region (around Venice).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Veneto is followed by the Emilia-Romagna region and by the Adriatic Croatian counties.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The Croatian tourist facilities are further augmented by 21,000 nautical ports and moorings; nautical tourists are attracted to various types of marine protected areas.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] As of January 2012, the Blue Flag has been awarded to 103 Italian Adriatic beaches and 29 marinas, 116 Croatian beaches and 19 marinas, 7 Slovenian beaches and 2 marinas, and 16 Montenegrin beaches.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Adriatic tourism is a significant source of income for these countries, especially in Croatia and Montenegro where the tourism income generated along the Adriatic coast represents the bulk of such income.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The direct contribution of travel and tourism to Croatia's GDP stood at 5.1% in 2011, with the total industry contribution estimated at 12.8% of the national GDP.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] For Montenegro, the direct contribution of tourism to the national GDP is 8.1%, with the total contribution to the economy at 17.2% of Montenegrin GDP.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Tourism in Adriatic Croatia has recently exhibited greater growth than in the other regions around the Adriatic.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] There are nineteen Adriatic Sea ports (in four different countries) that each handles more than a million tonnes of cargo per year.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The largest cargo ports among them are the Port of Trieste (the largest Adriatic cargo port in Italy), the Port of Venice, the Port of Ravenna, the Port of Koper (the largest Slovenian port), the Port of Rijeka (the largest Croatian cargo port), and the Port of Brindisi.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The largest passenger ports in the Adriatic are the Port of Split (the largest Croatian passenger port) and ports in Ancona (the largest Italian passenger seaport in the Adriatic).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The largest seaport in Montenegro is the Port of Bar.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In 2010, the Northern Adriatic seaports of Trieste, Venice, Ravenna, Koper and Rijeka founded the North Adriatic Ports Association to position themselves more favourably in the EU's transport systems.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The port of Trieste is of particular importance for Central Europe because this is where the Transalpine Pipeline begins, supplying 100 percent of southern Germany, 90 percent of Austria and 50 percent of the Czech Republic with crude oil.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Natural gas is produced through several projects, including a joint venture of the Eni and INA companies that operates two platforms—one is in Croatian waters and draws gas from six wells, and the other (which started operating in 2010) is located in Italian waters.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The Adriatic gas fields were discovered in the 1970s, but their development commenced in 1996.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In 2008, INA produced 14.58 million BOE per day of gas.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] About 100 offshore platforms are located in the Emilia-Romagna region, along with 17 in the Northern Adriatic.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Eni estimated its concessions in the Adriatic Sea to hold at least 40,000,000,000 cubic metres (1.4×1012 cu ft) of natural gas, adding that they may even reach 100,000,000,000 cubic metres (3.5×1012 cu ft).
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] INA estimates, however, are 50% lower than those supplied by Eni.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Oil was discovered in the Northern Adriatic at a depth of approximately 5,400 metres (17,700 ft); the discovery was assessed as not viable because of its location, depth and quality.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] These gas and oil reserves are part of the Po basin Province of Northern Italy and the Northern Mediterranean Sea.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In the 2000s, investigation works aimed at discovering gas and oil reserves in the Middle and Southern Adriatic basins intensified, and by the decade's end, oil and natural gas reserves were discovered southeast of the Bari, Brindisi—Rovesti and Giove oil discoveries.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Surveys indicate reserves of 3 billion barrels of oil in place and 5.7×1010 cubic metres (2,000,000,000,000 cu ft) of gas in place.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] The discovery was followed by further surveys off the Croatian coast.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] In January 2012, INA commenced prospecting for oil off Dubrovnik, marking the resumption of oil exploration along the eastern Adriatic coast after surveys commenced in the late 1980s around the island of Brač were cancelled because of Yugoslavia's breakup and war in Croatia.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] Montenegro is also expected to look for oil off its coast.
[src:ironclad-warship/adriatic-p02] As of January 2012, only 200 exploration wells had been sunk off the Croatian coast, with all but 30 in the Northern Adriatic basin.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] The ***Aetna*-class ironclad floating batteries** were built during the Crimean War for the attack of Russian coastal fortifications.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] Britain and France each laid down five of these coastal attack vessels in 1854.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] The French used three of their batteries in 1855 against the defences at Kinburn on the Black Sea, where they were effective against Russian shore defences.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] The British plan to use theirs in the Baltic Sea against Kronstadt in 1856 was influential in causing the Russians to sue for peace.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] The development of such iron-armoured batteries was a step towards the development of ironclad warships.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] One of the British batteries, *Trusty*, was used for trials in 1861 with a prototype rotating turret, based on Captain Cowper Phipps Coles' designs.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] Emperor Napoleon III initiated the design of armoured steam-powered batteries for the French Navy.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] The original idea was to protect the sides with boxes of cannonballs, but the British engineer Thomas Lloyd suggested using thick wrought iron plates instead.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] Trials at Vincennes showed that Lloyd's idea was more effective, so it was adopted.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] Napoleon wanted ten floating batteries built in time for the 1855 campaign, but as French industry could only build five in time, France's British allies were asked to build the other five.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] Unfortunately the First Lord, Sir James Graham, confused this concept with the unsuccessful iron-hulled frigates built in the late 1840s, and asked for further trials, so the British armoured batteries were not ordered until 4 October 1854.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] These vessels were copies of the French *Dévastation*-class batteries.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] The French batteries carried 16 guns, but had 24 gun ports.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] The British *Aetna* class were also intended to carry 16 guns, but the first four completed only carried 14 guns to reduce draught to 8 feet 8 inches (2.64 m).
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] The Admiralty design drawing showed them with 32 gunports.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] These ports were very large – 34 by 40 inches (0.86 by 1.02 m).
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] The wooden-hulled *Aetna* class had "straight vertical sides and a flat bottom with a very bluff bow and stern.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] Their armour plates, nominally 4 inches (102 mm), but in many cases were rolled 0.25–0.5 inches (6.4–12.7 mm) under thickness, were locked together with tongue and groove joints." The iron armour was supported by 20-inch-thick (510 mm) oak sides.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] The wooden upper deck was 9 inches (229 mm) thick.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] There were two conning towers protected by 5⁄8 inch (16 mm) wrought iron plate.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] In October 1858, experimental firing trials were undertaken against *Meteor* and one of the follow-on class of iron-hulled armoured batteries, *Erebus*.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] These demonstrated the importance of wooden backing for the armour, as *Meteor* put up far better resistance than *Erebus*, where the frames were displaced by concussion.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] The first four completed had two-cylinder 25.5 in (0.65 m) diameter 24 in (0.61 m) stroke horizontal single expansion engines of 150 nhp, which operated at 62 psi (430 kPa).
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] Although they were completed as single screw vessels, *Meteor* was altered to triple screw with wing-shafts; her trials with triple screw were 12 days after her trials with single screw.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] The most likely method of driving the wing shafts was a belt arrangement, which was common practice at the time.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] It is unclear whether any of the others were also altered to triple-screw.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] On trials with a single 6 ft (1.8 m) diameter, 12 ft 6 in (3.81 m) pitch screw, *Meteor* reached 5.7 kn (10.6 km/h) at 139 rpm with the safety valve set at 60 psi, and engine power was recorded as 530 ihp (400 kW).
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] On her trials fitted as triple screw, *Meteor* reached 5.25 knots (9.72 km/h) at 139 rpm.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] Engine power was recorded as 498 indicated horsepower (371 kW).
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] The two wing screws on this trial were 6 ft (1.8 m) diameter, 7 ft 6 in (2.29 m) pitch.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] The second *Aetna* had two-cylinder 27 in (0.69 m) diameter 30 in (0.76 m) stroke horizontal single expansion engines of 200 nhp.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] Her boilers were salvaged from the first *Aetna*.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] Admiralty records for *Meteor*, *Thunder*, *Glatton* and *Trusty* state that both the Mare and the Green yards were at Limehouse, other vessels built by Mare and by Green were built at Blackwall.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] It is possible that there is an error in the records, and they were actually built at Blackwall.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] The first *Aetna* was to have been launched on 5 May 1855, but caught fire on the building slip, and launched herself two days early.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] Her remains were broken up on the river-bank.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] Her replacement, the second *Aetna* was finished too late for the Crimean War, and was fitted for harbour service in 1866.
[src:ironclad-warship/aetna-class-ironclad-floating-battery] She burnt out at Sheerness in 1873 and was broken up in 1874.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] The **Mexican Navy paddle frigate *Guadalupe*** was the flagship of the Mexican Navy from 1842 to 1847.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] She participated in the Naval Battle of Campeche in 1843.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] She was one of the first iron-hulled (hull that was made of wood lined with an iron sheet) warships ever built and one of the first to see action in a naval battle.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] The Mexican Navy has its origins in the creation of the Ministry of War in 1821.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] From that year until 1939 it existed jointly with the Mexican Army in the organic ministry.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] Since its declaration of independence from Spain in September 1810, through the mid decades of the 19th century, Mexico found itself in a constant state of war, mostly against Spain which had not recognized its independence.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] Therefore, its priority was to purchase its first fleet from the U.S. in order to displace the last remaining Spanish forces from its coasts.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] The *Guadalupe*, probably named after the national patron, Our Lady of Guadalupe, was built in the Liverpool shipyard of Jonathan Laird of Birkenhead, England, in 1842.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] *Guadalupe* was referred to as a steam paddle frigate and had a full brig rig.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] *Guadalupe* was 183 feet in length with a displacement of 878 tons.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] She was the biggest iron warship in the world when built.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] Due to diplomatic action by the Republic of Texas she was delivered unarmed as a merchant ship with her guns in her hold.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] In May 1842, William Kennedy, the Republic of Texas' consul general in London, and Ashbel Smith, minister to England, protested the building of the vessels for Mexican use against Texas and urged the British government to detain them.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] Lord Aberdeen of the Foreign Office decided that arms might be placed on the vessels so long as they were not mounted in British ports, and *Guadaloupe* sailed in June despite Texan protests.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] Aberdeen insisted that the British would maintain strict neutrality in the struggle between Texas and Mexico and that no British military officer would be allowed to serve in the Mexican military against Texas.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] When she arrived in Mexico she was equipped with two 68-pounder Paixhans guns which fired explosive shells, two 32-pounder guns and two 24-pounder long guns.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] A feature that was unusual for the period was her construction with watertight compartmentation throughout her hull, a feature that impressed famous French naval architect Henri Dupuy de Lôme.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] She carried a crew that included many British nationals, led by her captain Edward Phillip Charlwood, Commander RN, who started while she was building in 1841 and who remained her captain until 1843.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] The Mexican fleet now possessed the paddle steam frigates *Guadalupe* and *Montezuma*.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] About 40 of the crew of the *Guadalupe* were sick with yellow fever.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] The Texas Navy commander Moore hoped to encounter the *Guadalupe* separate from her escort *Montezuma*.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] *Austin* and *Wharton* made for the Yucatán coast and encountered the Mexican squadron on 30 April 1843 between Lerma and Campeche.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] *Montezuma* and *Guadalupe*, along with four smaller vessels, comprised the Mexican fleet.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] The Texans were augmented by two Yucatecan ships and five small gunboats, but were clearly the smaller fleet.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] The Mexican shooting at first fell short and then went over the Texas ships.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] During the two-hour running battle the *Austin* was struck once in the fighting and lost some of her mizzen rigging and the *Guadalupe* had 7 dead and the *Montezuma* 13 dead.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] After a few hours, the Mexican sailing ships departed and only the two steamers remained.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] The result was that the Mexican blockade of the port of Campeche was lifted and the Texan ships put into the port for repairs.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] This first attack was a draw and the fleets separated.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] The next event on 16 May 1843 was orchestrated by Commodore Moore and his "Texians" who lured the Mexican Forces into a narrow roadstead, and hounded the Mexican ships away from the harbour firing most of Austin's ammunition as Wharton was not able to engage.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] The battle toll came out as; "Austin" 3 dead, "Wharton" 2 dead, "Montezuma" 40 dead including her captain and "Guadalupe" 47 dead.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] The Mexican Fleet was effectively incapacitated.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] This battle would represent the only time that steam-driven warships would be defeated by sail powered ships.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] There were numerous falsehoods circulated about Moore's battle with Guadalupe.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] These seem to be largely the confections of the press, egged on by politicians, and are not to be taken seriously.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] Her captain, Commander Edward P Charlwood, RN, had his own description of the action.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] He noted that compared to a wooden ship her damage from shot was much less in part to the action being in warm waters.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] During the 4 to 5 weeks of the Yucatán campaign she was hit a total of 6 times by 18- or 24-pounder solid shot.
[src:ironclad-warship/arm-guadalupe] He described *Guadalupe* as a good gun platform and felt that they had hit the Texan sloop-of-war Austin about 12 times with 68-pounder shells causing her to withdraw from the action of 16 May 1843.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] An **ironclad** was a steam-propelled warship protected by steel or iron armor constructed from 1859 to the early 1890s.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The ironclad was developed as a result of the vulnerability of wooden warships to explosive and incendiary shells.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The first ironclad battleship, *Gloire*, was launched by the French Navy in November 1859, narrowly preempting the British Royal Navy.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] However, Britain built the first completely iron-hulled warships.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Ironclads were first used in warfare in 1862 during the American Civil War, when they operated against wooden ships, and against each other at the Battle of Hampton Roads in Virginia.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Their performance demonstrated that the ironclad had replaced the unarmored ship of the line as the most powerful warship afloat.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Ironclad gunboats became very successful in the American Civil War.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Ironclads were designed for several uses, including as high-seas battleships, long-range cruisers, and coastal defense ships.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Rapid development of warship design in the late 19th century transformed the ironclad from a wooden-hulled vessel that carried sails to supplement its steam engines into the steel-built, turreted battleships and cruisers familiar in the 20th century.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] This change was pushed forward by the development of heavier naval guns, more sophisticated steam engines, and advances in ferrous metallurgy that made steel shipbuilding possible.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The quick pace of change meant that many ships were obsolete almost as soon as they were finished and that naval tactics were in a state of flux.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Many ironclads were built to make use of the naval ram, the torpedo, or sometimes both (as in the case with smaller ships and later torpedo boats), which several naval designers considered the important weapons of naval combat.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] There is no clear end to the ironclad period, but toward the end of the 1890s, the term *ironclad* dropped out of use.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] New ships were increasingly constructed to a standard pattern and designated as battleships or armored cruisers.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The ironclad became technically feasible and tactically necessary because of developments in shipbuilding in the first half of the 19th century.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Richard Hill: "The (ironclad) had three chief characteristics: a metal-skinned hull, steam propulsion and a main armament of guns capable of firing explosive shells.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] It is only when all three characteristics are present that a fighting ship can properly be called an ironclad." Each of these developments was introduced separately in the decade before the first ironclads.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] In the 18th and early 19th centuries, fleets had relied on two types of major warship, the ship of the line and the frigate.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The first major change to these types was the introduction of steam power for propulsion.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] While paddle steamer warships had been used from the 1830s onward, steam propulsion only became suitable for major warships after the adoption of the screw propeller in the 1840s.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Steam-powered screw frigates were built in the mid-1840s, and at the end of the decade the French Navy introduced steam power to its line of battle.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Napoleon III's ambition to gain greater influence in Europe required a sustained challenge to the British at sea.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The first purpose-built steam battleship was the 90-gun *Napoléon* in 1850.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] *Napoléon* was armed as a conventional ship-of-the-line, but her steam engines could give her a speed of 12 knots (22 km/h; 14 mph), regardless of the wind conditions: a potentially decisive advantage in a naval engagement.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The introduction of the steam ship-of-the-line led to a building competition between France and Britain.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Eight sister ships to *Napoléon* were built in France over a period of ten years, but the United Kingdom soon managed to take the lead in production.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Altogether, France built ten new wooden steam battleships and converted 28 from older ships of the line, while the United Kingdom built 18 and converted 41.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The era of the wooden steam ship-of-the-line was brief, because of new, more powerful naval guns.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] In the 1820s and 1830s, warships began to mount increasingly heavy guns, replacing 18- and 24-pounder guns with 32-pounders on sailing ships-of-the-line and introducing 68-pounders on steamers.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Then, the first shell guns firing explosive shells were introduced following their development by the French Général Henri-Joseph Paixhans.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] By the 1840s they were part of the standard armament for naval powers including the French Navy, Royal Navy, Imperial Russian Navy and United States Navy.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] It is often held that the power of explosive shells to smash wooden hulls, as demonstrated by the Russian destruction of an Ottoman squadron at the Battle of Sinop, spelled the end of the wooden-hulled warship.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The more practical threat to wooden ships was from conventional cannon firing red-hot shot, which could lodge in the hull and cause a fire or ammunition explosion.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Some navies even experimented with hollow shot filled with molten metal for extra incendiary power.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The use of wrought iron instead of wood as the primary material of ships' hulls began in the 1830s; the first "warship" with an iron hull was the gunboat *Nemesis*, built by Jonathan Laird of Birkenhead for the East India Company in 1839.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] There followed, also from Laird, the first full-sized warship with a metal hull, the 1842 steam frigate *Guadalupe* for the Mexican Navy.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The latter ship performed well during the Naval Battle of Campeche, with her captain reporting that he thought that there were fewer iron splinters from *Guadalupe*'s hull than from a wooden hull.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Encouraged by the positive reports of the iron hulls of those ships in combat, the Admiralty ordered a series of experiments to evaluate what happened when thin iron hulls were struck by projectiles, both solid shot and hollow shells, beginning in 1845 and lasting through 1851.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Critics like Lieutenant-general Sir Howard Douglas believed that the splinters from the hull were even more dangerous than those from wooden hulls and the tests partially confirmed this belief.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] What was ignored was that with 14 inches (356 mm) of wood backing, the iron would stop most of the splinters from penetrating and that relatively thin plates of iron backed by the same thickness of wood would generally cause shells to split open and fail to detonate.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The early experimental results seemed to support the critics and party politics came into play as the Whig First Russell ministry replaced the Tory Second Peel Ministry in 1846.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The new administration sided with the critics and ordered that the four iron-hulled propeller frigates ordered by the Tories be converted into troopships.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] No iron warships would be ordered until the beginning of the Crimean War in 1854.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Experiments made during the first half of 1854 proved highly satisfactory, and on 17 July 1854, the French communicated to the British Government that a solution had been found to make gun-proof vessels and that plans would be communicated.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] After tests in September 1854, the British Admiralty agreed to build five armored floating batteries on the French plans.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The French floating batteries were deployed in 1855 as a supplement to the wooden steam battle fleet in the Crimean War.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The role of the battery was to assist unarmored mortar and gunboats bombarding shore fortifications.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The French used three of their ironclad batteries (*Lave*, *Tonnante* and *Dévastation*) in 1855 against the defenses at the Battle of Kinburn on the Black Sea, where they were effective against Russian shore defences.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] They would later be used again during the Italian war in the Adriatic in 1859.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The British floating batteries *Glatton* and *Meteor* arrived too late to participate to the action at Kinburn.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The British planned to use theirs in the Baltic Sea against the well-fortified Russian naval base at Kronstadt.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The batteries have a claim to the title of the first ironclad warships but they were capable of only 4 knots (7.4 km/h; 4.6 mph) under their own power: they operated under their own power at the Battle of Kinburn, but had to be towed for long-range transit.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] They were also arguably marginal to the work of the navy.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The brief success of the floating ironclad batteries convinced France to begin work on armored warships for their battlefleet.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] By the end of the 1850s it was clear that France was unable to match British building of steam warships, and to regain the strategic initiative a dramatic change was required.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The result was the first ocean-going ironclad, *Gloire*, begun in 1857 and launched in 1859.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] *Gloire*'s wooden hull was modelled on that of a steam ship of the line, reduced to one deck, and sheathed in iron plates 4.5 inches (114 mm) thick.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] She was propelled by a steam engine, driving a single screw propeller for a speed of 13 knots (24 km/h; 15 mph).
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] She was armed with thirty-six 6.4-inch (160 mm) rifled guns.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] France proceeded to construct 16 ironclad warships, including two sister ships to *Gloire*, and the only two-decked broadside ironclads ever built, *Magenta* and *Solférino*.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The Royal Navy had not been keen to sacrifice its advantage in steam ships of the line, but was determined that the first British ironclad would outmatch the French ships in every respect, particularly speed.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] A fast ship would have the advantage of being able to choose a range of engagement that could make her invulnerable to enemy fire.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The British specification was more a large, powerful frigate than a ship-of-the-line.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The requirement for speed meant a very long vessel, which had to be built from iron.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The result was the construction of two *Warrior*-class ironclads; HMS *Warrior* and HMS *Black Prince*.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The ships had a successful design, though there were necessarily compromises between 'sea-keeping', strategic range and armor protection.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Their weapons were more effective than those of *Gloire*, and with the largest set of steam engines yet fitted to a ship, they could steam at 14.3 knots (26.5 km/h).
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Yet the *Gloire* and her sisters had full iron-armor protection along the waterline and the battery itself.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The British *Warrior* and *Black Prince* (but also the smaller *Defence* and *Resistance*) were obliged to concentrate their armor in a central "citadel" or "armoured box", leaving many main deck guns and the fore and aft sections of the vessel unprotected.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The use of iron in the construction of *Warrior*also came with some drawbacks; iron hulls required more regular and intensive repairs than wooden hulls, and iron was more susceptible to fouling by marine life.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] By 1862, navies across Europe had adopted ironclads.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Britain and France each had sixteen either completed or under construction, though the British vessels were larger.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Austria, Italy, Russia, and Spain were also building ironclads.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] However, the first battles using the new ironclad ships took place during the American Civil War, between Union and Confederate ships in 1862.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] These were markedly different from the broadside-firing, masted designs of *Gloire* and *Warrior*.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The clash of the Italian and Austrian fleets at the Battle of Lissa (1866), also had an important influence on the development of ironclad design.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The first use of ironclads in combat came in the U.S.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Navy at the time the war broke out had no ironclads, its most powerful ships being six unarmored steam-powered frigates.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Since the bulk of the Navy remained loyal to the Union, the Confederacy sought to gain advantage in the naval conflict by acquiring modern armored ships.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] In May 1861, the Confederate Congress appropriated $2 million dollars for the purchase of ironclads from overseas, and in July and August 1861 the Confederacy started work on construction and converting wooden ships.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] On 12 October 1861, CSS *Manassas* became the first ironclad to enter combat, when she fought Union warships on the Mississippi during the Battle of the Head of Passes.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] She had been converted from a commercial vessel in New Orleans for river and coastal fighting.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] In February 1862, the larger CSS *Virginia* joined the Confederate Navy, having been rebuilt at Norfolk.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Constructed on the hull of USS *Merrimack*, *Virginia* originally was a conventional warship made of wood, but she was converted into an iron-covered casemate ironclad gunship, when she entered the Confederate Navy.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] By this time, the Union had completed seven ironclad gunboats of the City class, and was about to complete USS *Monitor*, an innovative design proposed by the Swedish inventor John Ericsson.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The Union was also building a large armored frigate, USS *New Ironsides*, and the smaller USS *Galena*.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The first battle between ironclads happened on 9 March 1862, as the armored *Monitor* was deployed to protect the Union's wooden fleet from the ironclad ram *Virginia* and other Confederate warships.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] In this engagement, the second day of the Battle of Hampton Roads, the two ironclads tried to ram one another while shells bounced off their armor.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The battle attracted attention worldwide, making it clear that the wooden warship was now out of date, with the ironclads destroying them easily.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The Civil War saw more ironclads built by both sides, and they played an increasing role in the naval war alongside the unarmored warships, commerce raiders and blockade runners.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The Union built a large fleet of fifty monitors modeled on their namesake.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Only CSS *Stonewall* was completed, and she arrived in Cuban waters just in time for the end of the war.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Through the remainder of the war, ironclads saw action in the Union's attacks on Confederate ports.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Seven Union monitors, including USS *Montauk*, as well as two other ironclads, the armored frigate *New Ironsides* and a light-draft USS *Keokuk*, participated in the failed attack on Charleston; one was sunk.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Two small ironclads, CSS *Palmetto State* and CSS *Chicora* participated in the defense of the harbor.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] For the later attack at Mobile Bay, the Union assembled four monitors as well as 11 wooden ships, facing the CSS *Tennessee*, the Confederacy's most powerful ironclad, and three gunboats.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] On the western front, the Union built a formidable force of river ironclads, beginning with several converted riverboats and then contracting engineer James Eads of St.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Louis, Missouri to build the City-class ironclads.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] These excellent ships were built with twin engines and a central paddle wheel, all protected by an armored casemate.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] They had a shallow draft, allowing them to journey up smaller tributaries, and were very well suited for river operations.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Eads also produced monitors for use on the rivers, the first two of which differed from the ocean-going monitors in that they contained a paddle wheel (USS *Neosho* and USS *Osage*).
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The Union ironclads played an important role in the Mississippi and tributaries by providing tremendous fire upon Confederate forts, installations and vessels with relative impunity to enemy fire.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] They were not as heavily armored as the ocean-going monitors of the Union, but they were adequate for their intended use.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] More Western Flotilla Union ironclads were sunk by torpedoes (mines) than by enemy fire, and the most damaging fire for the Union ironclads was from shore installations, not Confederate vessels.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The first fleet battle, and the first ocean battle, involving ironclad warships was the Battle of Lissa in 1866.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Waged between the Austrian and Italian navies, the battle pitted combined fleets of wooden frigates and corvettes and ironclad warships on both sides in the largest naval battle between the battles of Navarino and Tsushima.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The Italian fleet consisted of 12 ironclads and a similar number of wooden warships, escorting transports which carried troops intending to land on the Adriatic island of Lissa.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Among the Italian ironclads were seven broadside ironclad frigates, four smaller ironclads, and the newly built *Affondatore* – a double-turreted ram.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Opposing them, the Austrian navy had seven ironclad frigates.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The Austrians believed their ships to have less effective guns than their enemy, so decided to engage the Italians at close range and ram them.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The Austrian fleet formed into an arrowhead formation with the ironclads in the first line, charging at the Italian ironclad squadron.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] In the melée which followed both sides were frustrated by the lack of damage inflicted by guns, and by the difficulty of ramming—nonetheless, the effective ramming attack being made by the Austrian flagship against the Italian attracted great attention in following years.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The superior Italian fleet lost its two ironclads, *Re d'Italia* and *Palestro*, while the Austrian unarmored screw two-decker SMS *Kaiser* remarkably survived close actions with four Italian ironclads.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The battle ensured the popularity of the ram as a weapon in European ironclads for many years, and the victory won by Austria established it as the predominant naval power in the Adriatic.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The battles of the American Civil War and at Lissa were very influential on the designs and tactics of the ironclad fleets that followed.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] In particular, it taught a generation of naval officers the (ultimately erroneous) lesson that ramming was the best way to sink enemy ironclads.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The adoption of iron armor meant that the traditional naval armament of dozens of light cannon became useless, since their shot would bounce off an armored hull.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] To penetrate armor, increasingly heavy guns were mounted on ships; nevertheless, the view that ramming was the only way to sink an ironclad became widespread.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The increasing size and weight of guns also meant a movement away from the ships mounting many guns broadside, in the manner of a ship-of-the-line, towards a handful of guns in turrets for all-round fire.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] From the 1860s to the 1880s many naval designers believed that the ram was again a vital weapon in naval warfare.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] With steam power freeing ships from the wind, iron construction increasing their structural strength, and armor making them invulnerable to shellfire, the ram seemed to offer the opportunity to strike a decisive blow.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The scant damage inflicted by the guns of *Monitor* and *Virginia* at Hampton Roads and the spectacular but lucky success of the Austrian flagship SMS *Erzherzog Ferdinand Max* sinking the Italian *Re d'Italia* at Lissa gave strength to the ramming craze.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] From the early 1870s to early 1880s most British naval officers thought that guns were about to be replaced as the main naval armament by the ram.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Those who noted the tiny number of ships that had actually been sunk by ramming struggled to be heard.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The revival of ramming had a significant effect on naval tactics.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Since the 17th century the predominant tactic of naval warfare had been the line of battle, where a fleet formed a long line to give it the best fire from its broadside guns.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] This tactic was totally unsuited to ramming, and the ram threw fleet tactics into disarray.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The question of how an ironclad fleet should deploy in battle to make best use of the ram was never tested in battle, and if it had been, combat might have shown that rams could only be used against ships which were already stopped dead in the water.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The ram finally fell out of favor in the 1880s, as the same effect could be achieved with a torpedo, with less vulnerability to quick-firing guns.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The armament of ironclads tended to become concentrated in a small number of powerful guns capable of penetrating the armor of enemy ships at range; calibre and weight of guns increased markedly to achieve greater penetration.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Throughout the ironclad era navies also grappled with the complexities of rifled versus smoothbore guns and breech-loading versus muzzle-loading.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] HMS *Warrior* carried a mixture of 110-pounder 7-inch (178 mm) breech-loading rifles and more traditional 68-pounder smoothbore guns.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] *Warrior* highlighted the challenges of picking the right armament; the breech-loaders she carried, designed by Sir William Armstrong, were intended to be the next generation of heavy armament for the Royal Navy, but were shortly withdrawn from service.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Breech-loading guns seemed to offer important advantages.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] A breech-loader could be reloaded without moving the gun, a lengthy process particularly if the gun then needed to be re-aimed.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] *Warrior*'s Armstrong guns also had the virtue of being lighter than an equivalent smoothbore and, because of their rifling, more accurate.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Nonetheless, the design was rejected because of problems which plagued breech-loaders for decades.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The weakness of the breech-loader was the obvious problem of sealing the breech.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] All guns are powered by the explosive conversion of a solid propellant into gas.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] This explosion propels the shot or shell out of the front of the gun, but also imposes great stresses on the gun-barrel.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] If the breech—which experiences some of the greatest forces in the gun—is not entirely secure, then there is a risk that either gas will discharge through the breech or that the breech will break.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] This in turn reduces the muzzle velocity of the weapon and can also endanger the gun crew.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] *Warrior*'s Armstrong guns suffered from both problems; the shells were unable to penetrate the 4.5-inch (114 mm) armor of *Gloire*, while sometimes the screw which closed the breech flew backwards out of the gun on firing.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Similar problems were experienced with the breech-loading guns which became standard in the French and German navies.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] These problems influenced the British to equip ships with muzzle-loading weapons of increasing power until the 1880s.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] After a brief introduction of the 100-pounder or 9.2-inch (230 mm) smoothbore Somerset Gun, which weighed 6.5 long tons (6.6 t), the Admiralty introduced 7-inch (178 mm) rifled guns, weighing 7 long tons (7 t).
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] These were followed by a series of increasingly mammoth weapons—guns weighing 12 long tons (12 t), 18 long tons (18 t), 25 long tons (25 t), 38 long tons (39 t) and finally 81 long tons (82 t), with caliber increasing from 8 inches (203 mm) to 16 inches (406 mm).
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The decision to retain muzzle-loaders until the 1880s has been criticized by historians.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] However, at least until the late 1870s, the British muzzle-loaders had superior performance in terms of both range and rate of fire than the French and Prussian breech-loaders, which suffered from the same problems as the first Armstrong guns.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] From 1875 onwards, the balance between breech- and muzzle-loading changed.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Captain de Bange invented a method of reliably sealing a breech, adopted by the French in 1873.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Just as compellingly, the growing size of naval guns and consequently, their ammunition, made muzzle-loading much more complicated.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] With guns of such size there was no prospect of hauling in the gun for reloading, or even reloading by hand, and complicated hydraulic systems were required for reloading the gun outside the turret without exposing the crew to enemy fire.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] In 1882, the 81-ton, 16-inch guns of HMS *Inflexible* fired only once every 11 minutes while bombarding Alexandria during the Urabi Revolt.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The 102-long-ton (104 t), 450 mm (17.72 inch) guns of the *Duilio* class could each fire a round every 15 minutes.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] In the Royal Navy, the switch to breech-loaders was finally made in 1879; as well as the significant advantages in terms of performance, opinion was swayed by an explosion on board HMS *Thunderer* caused by a gun being double-loaded, a problem which could only happen with a muzzle-loading gun.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The caliber and weight of guns could only increase so far.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The larger the gun, the slower it would be to load, the greater the stresses on the ship's hull, and the less the stability of the ship.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The size of the gun peaked in the 1880s, with some of the heaviest calibers of gun ever used at sea.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] HMS *Benbow* carried two 16.25-inch (413 mm) breech-loading guns, each weighing 110 long tons (112 t).
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] A few years afterwards, the Italians used 450 mm (17.72 inch) muzzle-loading guns on the *Duilio* class ships.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] American ordnance experts accordingly preferred smoothbore monsters whose round shot could at least 'skip' along the surface of the water.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Actual effective combat ranges, they had learned during the Civil War, were comparable to those in the Age of Sail—though a vessel could now be smashed to pieces in only a few rounds.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Smoke and the general chaos of battle only added to the problem.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] As a result, many naval engagements in the 'Age of the Ironclad' were still fought at ranges within easy eyesight of their targets, and well below the maximum reach of their ships' guns.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Another method of increasing firepower was to vary the projectile fired or the nature of the propellant.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Early ironclads used black powder, which expanded rapidly after combustion; this meant cannons had relatively short barrels, to prevent the barrel itself slowing the shell.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The sharpness of the black powder explosion also meant that guns were subjected to extreme stress.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] One important step was to press the powder into pellets, allowing a slower, more controlled explosion and a longer barrel.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] A further step forward was the introduction of chemically different brown powder which combusted more slowly again.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] It also put less stress on the insides of the barrel, allowing guns to last longer and to be manufactured to tighter tolerances.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The development of smokeless powder, based on nitroglycerine or nitrocellulose, by the French inventor Paul Vielle in 1884 was a further step allowing smaller charges of propellant with longer barrels.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The guns of the pre-Dreadnought battleships of the 1890s tended to be smaller in caliber compared to the ships of the 1880s, most often 12 in (305 mm), but progressively grew in length of barrel, making use of improved propellants to gain greater muzzle velocity.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The nature of the projectiles also changed during the ironclad period.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Initially, the best armor-piercing projectile was a solid cast-iron shot.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Later, shot of chilled iron, a harder iron alloy, gave better armor-piercing qualities.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Eventually the armor-piercing shell was developed.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The first British, French and Russian ironclads, in a logical development of warship design from the long preceding era of wooden ships of the line, carried their weapons in a single line along their sides and so were called "broadside ironclads".
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Both *Gloire* and HMS *Warrior* were examples of this type.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Because their armor was so heavy, they could only carry a single row of guns along the main deck on each side rather than a row on each deck.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] A significant number of broadside ironclads were built in the 1860s, principally in Britain and France, but in smaller numbers by other powers including Italy, Austria, Russia and the United States.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The advantages of mounting guns on both broadsides was that the ship could engage more than one adversary at a time, and the rigging did not impede the field of fire.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Broadside armament also had disadvantages, which became more serious as ironclad technology developed.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Heavier guns to penetrate ever-thicker armor meant that fewer guns could be carried.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Furthermore, the adoption of ramming as an important tactic meant the need for ahead and all-round fire.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] These problems led to broadside designs being superseded by designs that gave greater all-round fire, which included central-battery, turret, and barbette designs.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] There were two main design alternatives to the broadside.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] In one design, the guns were placed in an armored casemate amidships: this arrangement was called the 'box-battery' or 'center-battery'.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] In the other, the guns could be placed on a rotating platform to give them a broad field of fire; when fully armored, this arrangement was called a turret and when partially armored or unarmored, a barbette.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The centre-battery was the simpler and, during the 1860s and 1870s, the more popular method.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Concentrating guns amidships meant the ship could be shorter and handier than a broadside type.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The first full-scale center-battery ship was HMS *Bellerophon* of 1865; the French laid down centre-battery ironclads in 1865 which were not completed until 1870.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Centre-battery ships often, but not always, had a recessed freeboard enabling some of their guns to fire directly ahead.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The turret was first used in naval combat on USS *Monitor* in 1862, with a type of turret designed by the Swedish engineer John Ericsson.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] A competing turret design was proposed by the British inventor Cowper Coles with a prototype of this installed on HMS *Trusty* in 1861 for testing and evaluation purposes.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Ericsson's turret turned on a central spindle, and Coles's turned on a ring of bearings.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Turrets offered the maximum arc of fire for the guns, but there were significant problems with their use in the 1860s.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The fire arc of a turret would be considerably limited by masts and rigging, so they were unsuited to use on the earlier ocean-going ironclads.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The second problem was that turrets were extremely heavy.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Ericsson was able to offer the heaviest possible turret (guns and armor protection) by deliberately designing a ship with very low freeboard.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The weight thus saved from having a high broadside above the waterline was diverted to actual guns and armor.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Low freeboard, however, also meant a smaller hull and therefore a smaller capacity for coal storage—and therefore range of the vessel.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] In many respects, the turreted, low-freeboard *Monitor* and the broadside sailor HMS *Warrior* represented two opposite extremes in what an 'Ironclad' was all about.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The most dramatic attempt to compromise these two extremes, or 'squaring this circle', was designed by Captain Cowper Phipps Coles: HMS *Captain*.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] It was a dangerously low freeboard turret ship, which nevertheless carried a full rig of sail and subsequently capsized not long after her launch in 1870.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Her half-sister HMS *Monarch* was restricted to firing from her turrets only on the port and starboard beams.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The third Royal Navy ship to combine turrets and masts was HMS *Inflexible* of 1876, which carried two turrets on either side of the center-line, allowing both to fire fore, aft and broadside.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] A lighter alternative to the turret, particularly popular with the French navy, was the barbette.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] These were fixed armored towers which held a gun on a turntable.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The crew was sheltered from direct fire, but vulnerable to plunging fire, for instance from shore emplacements.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The barbette was lighter than the turret, needing less machinery and no roof armor.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Some barbettes were stripped of their armor plate to reduce the top-weight of their ships.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The barbette became widely adopted in the 1880s, and with the addition of an armored 'gun-house', transformed into the turrets of the pre-dreadnought battleships.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The ironclad age saw the development of explosive torpedoes as naval weapons, which helped complicate the design and tactics of ironclad fleets.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The first torpedoes were static mines, used extensively in the American Civil War.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] That conflict also saw the development of the spar torpedo, an explosive charge pushed against the hull of a warship by a small boat.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] For the first time, a large warship faced a serious threat from a smaller one—and given the relative inefficiency of shellfire against ironclads, the threat from the spar torpedo was taken seriously.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Navy converted four of its monitors to become turretless armored spar-torpedo vessels while under construction in 1864–1865, but these vessels never saw action.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Another proposal, the towed or 'Harvey' torpedo, involved an explosive on a line or outrigger; either to deter a ship from ramming or to make a torpedo attack by a boat less suicidal.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] A more practical and influential weapon was the self-propelled or Whitehead torpedo.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Invented in 1868 and deployed in the 1870s, it formed part of the armament of ironclads of the 1880s like HMS *Inflexible* and the Italian *Duilio* class.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The ironclad's vulnerability to the torpedo was a key part of the critique of armored warships made by the *Jeune Ecole* school of naval thought; it appeared that any ship armored enough to prevent destruction by gunfire would be slow enough to be easily caught by torpedo.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] In practice, however, the *Jeune Ecole* was only briefly influential and the torpedo formed part of the confusing mixture of weapons possessed by ironclads.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The first ironclads were built on wooden or iron hulls, and protected by wrought iron armor backed by thick wooden planking.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Ironclads were still being built with wooden hulls into the 1870s.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Using wrought iron construction for warships offered advantages for the engineering of the hull.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] However, unarmored iron had many military disadvantages, and offered technical problems which kept wooden hulls in use for many years, particularly for long-range cruising warships.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Iron ships had first been proposed for military use in the 1820s.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] In the 1830s and 1840s, France, Britain and the United States had all experimented with iron-hulled but unarmored gunboats and frigates.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] However, the iron-hulled frigate was abandoned by the end of the 1840s, because iron hulls were more vulnerable to solid shot; iron was more brittle than wood, and iron frames more likely to fall out of shape than wood.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The unsuitability of unarmored iron for warship hulls meant that iron was only adopted as a building material for battleships when protected by armor.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] However, iron gave the naval architect many advantages.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Iron allowed larger ships and more flexible design, for instance the use of watertight bulkheads on the lower decks.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] *Warrior*, built of iron, was longer and faster than the wooden-hulled *Gloire*.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Iron could be produced to order and used immediately, in contrast to the need to give wood a long period of seasoning.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] And, given the large quantities of wood required to build a steam warship and the falling cost of iron, iron hulls were increasingly cost-effective.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The main reason for the French use of wooden hulls for the ironclad fleet built in the 1860s was that the French iron industry could not supply enough, and the main reason why Britain built its handful of wooden-hulled ironclads was to make best use of hulls already started and wood already bought.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Wooden hulls continued to be used for long-range and smaller ironclads, because iron nevertheless had a significant disadvantage.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Iron hulls suffered quick fouling by marine life, slowing the ships down—manageable for a European battlefleet close to dry docks, but a difficulty for long-range ships.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The only solution was to sheath the iron hull first in wood and then in copper, a laborious and expensive process which made wooden construction remain attractive.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Iron and wood were to some extent interchangeable: the Japanese *Kongō* and *Hiei* ordered in 1875 were sister-ships, but one was built of iron and the other of composite construction.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] After 1872, steel started to be introduced as a material for construction.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Compared to iron, steel allows for greater structural strength for a lower weight.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The French Navy led the way with the use of steel in its fleet, starting with the *Redoutable*, laid down in 1873 and launched in 1876.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] *Redoutable* nonetheless had wrought iron armor plate, and part of her exterior hull was iron rather than steel.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Even though Britain led the world in steel production, the Royal Navy was slow to adopt steel warships.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The Bessemer process for steel manufacture produced too many imperfections for large-scale use on ships.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] French manufacturers used the Siemens-Martin process to produce adequate steel, but British technology lagged behind.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The first all-steel warships built by the Royal Navy were the dispatch vessels *Iris* and *Mercury*, laid down in 1875 and 1876.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Iron-built ships used wood as part of their protection scheme.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] HMS *Warrior* was protected by 4.5 in (114 mm) of wrought iron backed by 15 in (381 mm) of teak, the strongest shipbuilding wood.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The wood played two roles, preventing spalling and also preventing the shock of a hit damaging the structure of the ship.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Later, wood and iron were combined in 'sandwich' armor, for instance in HMS *Inflexible*.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Steel was also an obvious material for armor.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] It was tested in the 1860s, but the steel of the time was too brittle and disintegrated when struck by shells.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Steel became practical to use when a way was found to fuse steel onto wrought iron plates, giving a form of compound armor.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] This compound armor was used by the British in ships built from the late 1870s, first for turret armor (starting with HMS *Inflexible*) and then for all armor (starting with HMS *Colossus* of 1882).
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The French and German navies adopted the innovation almost immediately, with licenses being given for the use of the 'Wilson System' of producing fused armor.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The first ironclads to have all-steel armor were the two ships of the *Duilio* class.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Though the ships were laid down in 1873 their armor was not purchased from France until 1877.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The French navy decided in 1880 to adopt compound armor for its fleet, but found it limited in supply, so from 1884 the French navy was using steel armor.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Britain stuck to compound armor until 1889.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The ultimate ironclad armor was case hardened nickel-steel.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Navy tested steel armor hardened by the Harvey process and found it superior to compound armor.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] For several years 'Harvey steel' was the state of the art, produced in the U.S., France, Germany, Britain, Austria and Italy.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] In 1894, the German firm Krupp developed gas cementing, which further hardened steel armor.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The German *Kaiser Friedrich III*, laid down in 1895, was the first ship to benefit from the new 'Krupp armor' and the new armor was quickly adopted; the Royal Navy using it from HMS *Canopus*, laid down in 1896.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] By 1901 almost all new battleships used Krupp armor, though the U.S. continued to use Harvey armor alongside until the end of the decade.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The equivalent strengths of the different armor plates was as follows: 15 in (381 mm) of wrought iron was equivalent to 12 in (305 mm) of either plain steel or compound iron and steel armor, and to 7.75 in (197 mm) of Harvey armor or 5.75 in (146 mm) of Krupp armor.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Ironclad construction also prefigured the later debate in battleship design between tapering and 'all-or-nothing' armor design.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] *Warrior* was only semi-armored, and could have been disabled by hits on the bow and stern.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] As the thickness of armor grew to protect ships from the increasingly heavy guns, the area of the ship which could be fully protected diminished.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] *Inflexible*'s armor protection was largely limited to the central citadel amidships, protecting boilers and engines, turrets and magazines, and little else.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] An ingenious arrangement of cork-filled compartments and watertight bulkheads was intended to keep her stable and afloat in the event of damage to her un-armored sections.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The first ocean-going ironclads carried masts and sails like their wooden predecessors, and these features were only gradually abandoned.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Early steam engines were inefficient; the wooden steam fleet of the Royal Navy could only carry "5 to 9 days coal", and the situation was similar with the early ironclads.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] *Warrior* also illustrates two design features which aided hybrid propulsion; she had retractable screws to reduce drag while under sail (though in practice the steam engine was run at a low throttle), and a telescopic funnel which could be folded down to the deck level.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Ships designed for coastal warfare, like the floating batteries of the Crimea, or USS *Monitor* and her sisters, dispensed with masts from the beginning.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The British HMS *Devastation*, started in 1869, was the first large, ocean-going ironclad to dispense with masts.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Her principal role was for combat in the English Channel and other European waters; while her coal supplies gave her enough range to cross the Atlantic, she would have had little endurance on the other side of the ocean.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The *Devastation* and the similar ships commissioned by the British and Russian navies in the 1870s were the exception rather than the rule.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Most ironclads of the 1870s retained masts, and only the Italian navy, which during that decade was focused on short-range operations in the Adriatic, built consistently mastless ironclads.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] During the 1860s, steam engines improved with the adoption of double-expansion steam engines, which used 30–40% less coal than earlier models.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The Royal Navy decided to switch to the double-expansion engine in 1871, and by 1875 they were widespread.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] However, this development alone was not enough to herald the end of the mast.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Whether this was due to a conservative desire to retain sails, or was a rational response to the operational and strategic situation, is a matter of debate.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] A steam-only fleet would require a network of coaling stations worldwide, which would need to be fortified at great expense to stop them falling into enemy hands.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Just as significantly, because of unsolved problems with the technology of the boilers which provided steam for the engines, the performance of double-expansion engines was rarely as good in practice as it was in theory.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] During the 1870s the distinction grew between 'first-class ironclads' or 'battleships' on the one hand, and 'cruising ironclads' designed for long-range work on the other.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The demands on first-class ironclads for very heavy armor and armament meant increasing displacement, which reduced speed under sail; and the fashion for turrets and barbettes made a sailing rig increasingly inconvenient.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] HMS *Inflexible*, launched in 1876 but not commissioned until 1881, was the last British battleship to carry masts, and these were widely seen as a mistake.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The start of the 1880s saw the end of sailing rig on ironclad battleships.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Sails persisted on 'cruising ironclads' for much longer.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] During the 1860s, the French navy had produced the *Alma* and *La Galissonnière* classes as small, long-range ironclads as overseas cruisers and the British had responded with ships like HMS *Swiftsure* of 1870.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The Russian ship *General-Admiral*, laid down in 1870 and completed in 1875, was a model of a fast, long-range ironclad which was likely to be able to outrun and outfight ships like *Swiftsure*.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Even the later HMS *Shannon*, often described as the first British armored cruiser, would have been too slow to outrun *General-Admiral*.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] While *Shannon* was the last British ship with a retractable propeller, later armored cruisers of the 1870s retained sailing rig, sacrificing speed under steam in consequence.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] It took until 1881 for the Royal Navy to lay down a long-range armored warship capable of catching enemy commerce raiders, HMS *Warspite*, which was completed in 1888.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] While sailing rigs were obsolescent for all purposes by the end of the 1880s, rigged ships were in service until the early years of the 20th century.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] The final evolution of ironclad propulsion was the adoption of the triple-expansion steam engine, a further refinement which was first adopted in HMS *Sans Pareil*, laid down in 1885 and commissioned in 1891.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p01] Many ships also used a forced draught to get additional power from their engines, and this system was widely used until the introduction of the steam turbine in the middle of the first decade of the Twentieth Century.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] While ironclads spread rapidly in navies worldwide, there were few pitched naval battles involving ironclads.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] Most European nations settled differences on land, and the Royal Navy struggled to maintain a deterrent parity with at least France, while providing suitable protection to Britain's commerce and colonial outposts worldwide.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] Ironclads remained, for the British Royal Navy, a matter of defending the British Isles first and projecting power abroad second.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] Those naval engagements of the latter half of the 19th century which involved ironclads normally involved colonial actions or clashes between second-rate naval powers.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] But these encounters were often enough to convince British policy-makers of the increasing hazards of strictly naval foreign intervention, from Hampton Roads in the American Civil War to the hardening combined defences of naval arsenals such as Kronstadt and Cherbourg.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] The United Kingdom possessed the largest navy in the world for the whole of the ironclad period.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] The Royal Navy was the second to adopt ironclad warships, and it applied them worldwide in their whole range of roles.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] In the age of sail, the British strategy for war depended on the Royal Navy mounting a blockade of the ports of the enemy.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] Because of the limited endurance of steamships, this was no longer possible, so the British at times considered the risk-laden plan of engaging an enemy fleet in harbor as soon as war broke out.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] To this end, the Royal Navy developed a series of 'coast-defense battleships', starting with the *Devastation* class.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] These 'breastwork monitors' were markedly different from the other high-seas ironclads of the period and were an important precursor of the modern battleship.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] As long-range monitors they could reach Bermuda unescorted, for example.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] However, they were still armed with only four heavy guns and were as vulnerable to mines and obstructions (and enemy monitors) as the original monitors of the Union Navy proved to be during the Civil War.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] The British prepared for an overwhelming mortar bombardment of Kronstadt by the close of the Crimean War, but never considered running the smoke-ridden, shallow-water gauntlet straight to St.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] Likewise, monitors proved acutely unable to 'overwhelm' enemy fortifications single-handed during the American conflict, though their low-profile and heavy armor protection made them ideal for running artillery gauntlets.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] Mines and obstructions negated these advantages—a problem the British Admiralty frequently acknowledged but never countered throughout the period.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] The British never laid down enough *Devastation*-class 'battleships' to instantly overwhelm Cherbourg, Kronstadt or even New York City with gunfire.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] This standard provoked aggressive shipbuilding in the 1880s and 1890s.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] British ships did not participate in any major wars in the ironclad period.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] The Royal Navy's ironclads only saw action as part of colonial battles or one-sided engagements like the bombardment of Alexandria in 1882.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] Defending British interests against Ahmed 'Urabi's Egyptian revolt, a British fleet opened fire on the fortifications around the port of Alexandria.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] A mixture of centre-battery and turret ships bombarded Egyptian positions for most of a day, forcing the Egyptians to retreat; return fire from Egyptian guns was heavy at first, but inflicted little damage, killing only five British sailors.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] Few Egyptian guns were actually dismounted, on the other hand, and the fortifications themselves were typically left intact.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] Had the Egyptians actually utilised the heavy mortars that were at their disposal, they might have quickly turned the tide, for the attacking British ironclads found it easy (for accuracy's sake) to simply anchor whilst firing—perfect targets for high-angle fire upon their thinly armored topdecks.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] The French navy built the first ironclad to try to gain a strategic advantage over the British, but were consistently out-built by the British.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] Despite taking the lead with a number of innovations like breech-loading weapons and steel construction, the French navy could never match the size of the Royal Navy.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] In the 1870s, the construction of ironclads ceased for a while in France as the Jeune Ecole school of naval thought took prominence, suggesting that torpedo boats and unarmored cruisers would be the future of warships.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] Like the British, the French navy saw little action with its ironclads; the French blockade of Germany in the Franco-Prussian War was ineffective, as the war was settled entirely on land.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] Russia built a number of ironclads, generally copies of British or French designs.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] Nonetheless, there were real innovations from Russia; the first true type of ironclad armored cruiser, *General-Admiral* of the 1870s, and a set of unusual but moderately-successful circular battleships referred to as "popovkas" (for Admiral Popov, who conceived the design).
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] The Russian Navy pioneered the wide-scale use of torpedo boats during the Russo-Turkish War of 1877–1878, mainly out of necessity because of the superior numbers and quality of ironclads used by the Turkish navy.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] Russia expanded her navy in the 1880s and 1890s with modern armored cruisers and battleships, but the ships were manned by inexperienced crews and politically appointed leadership, which enhanced their defeat in the Battle of Tsushima on 27 May 1905.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] The US Navy ended the Civil War with about fifty monitor-type coastal ironclads; by the 1870s most of these were laid up in reserve, leaving the United States virtually without an ironclad fleet.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] Another five large monitors were ordered in the 1870s.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] The limitations of the monitor type effectively prevented the US from projecting power overseas, and until the 1890s the United States would have come off badly in a conflict with even Spain or the Latin American powers.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] The 1890s saw the beginning of what became the Great White Fleet, and it was the modern pre-Dreadnoughts and armored cruisers built in the 1890s which defeated the Spanish fleet in the Spanish–American War of 1898.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] This started a new era of naval warfare.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] Ironclads were widely used in South America.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] Both sides used ironclads in the Chincha Islands War between Spain and the combined forces of Peru and Chile in the early 1860s.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] The powerful Spanish *Numancia* participated in the Battle of Callao but was unable to inflict significant damage upon the Callao defences.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] *Numancia*, was the first ironclad to circumnavigate the world under the command of Juan Bautista Antequera y Bobadilla de Eslava, arriving in Cádiz on 20 September 1867, and earning the motto: "Enloricata navis que primo terram circuivit" ["First ironclad ship to sail around the world"]).
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] In the War of the Pacific in 1879, both Peru and Chile had ironclad warships, including some of those used a few years previously against Spain.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] While *Independencia* ran aground early on, the Peruvian ironclad *Huáscar* made a great impact against Chilean shipping, delaying Chilean ground invasion by six months.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] She was eventually caught by two more modern Chilean centre-battery ironclads, *Blanco Encalada* and *Almirante Cochrane* at the Battle of Angamos Point.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] Ironclads were also used from the inception of the Imperial Japanese Navy (IJN).
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] *Kōtetsu* (Japanese: 甲鉄, literally "Ironclad", later renamed Azuma 東, "East") had a decisive role in the Naval Battle of Hakodate Bay in May 1869, which marked the end of the Boshin War, and the complete establishment of the Meiji Restoration.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] The IJN continued to develop its strength and commissioned a number of warships from British and European shipyards, first ironclads and later armored cruisers.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] These ships engaged the Chinese Beiyang fleet which was superior on paper at least at the Battle of the Yalu River.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] Thanks to superior short-range firepower, the Japanese fleet came off better, sinking or severely damaging eight ships and receiving serious damage to only four.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] The naval war was concluded the next year at the Battle of Weihaiwei, where the strongest remaining Chinese ships were surrendered to the Japanese.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] There is no clearly defined end to the ironclad, besides the transition from wood hulls to all-metal.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] Ironclads continued to be used in World War I.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] Towards the end of the 19th century, the descriptions 'battleship' and 'armored cruiser' came to replace the term 'ironclad'.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] The proliferation of ironclad battleship designs came to an end in the 1890s as navies reached a consensus on the design of battleships, producing the type known as the pre-dreadnought.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] These ships are sometimes covered in treatments of the ironclad warship.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] The next evolution of battleship design, the dreadnought, is never referred to as an 'ironclad'.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] Wells coined the term *The Land Ironclads* in a short story published in 1903, to describe fictional large armored fighting vehicles moving on pedrail wheels.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] The Ironclad Hotel in the town of Marble Bar, Australia was named after its resemblance to the warships.
[src:ironclad-warship/ironclad-warship-p02] A number of ironclads have been preserved or reconstructed as museum ships.
